## Chapter 1 (continued): The Big Debt Cycle

### The Five Stages of the Big Debt Cycle

The **Big Debt Cycle** progresses like a disease through identifiable stages. The cycle moves from sound/hard money and credit to increasingly loose money and credit, then to a debt bust requiring a return to sound/hard money and credit. The progression follows this sequence:

1. **Private sector** borrows healthily, then overborrows and has payment problems
2. **Government sector** tries to help, then overborrows and has payment problems
3. **Central bank** tries to help by "printing money" and buying government debt, then has problems paying it back
4. Central bank monetizes more debt if the debt is denominated in a currency it can print

### Stage 1: The Sound Money Stage

**When net debt levels are low, money is sound, the country is competitive, and debt growth fuels productivity growth, which creates incomes more than enough to pay back the debts. This leads to increases in financial wealth and confidence.**

#### Money vs. Credit

- **Credit** is a promise to deliver money. Unlike credit, which requires payment later, **money settles transactions immediately** — if money is given, the transaction is complete; if credit is given, money is owed
- Anyone can create credit, but not anyone can create money
- Credit grows easily, so there is much more credit than money
- The most effective money is both a medium of exchange and a **storehold of wealth** that is widely accepted around the world

#### Hard vs. Paper Money

- At the early stage of the Big Debt Cycle, money is "hard" — a medium of exchange that is also a storehold of wealth that can't easily be increased in supply
- Examples: **gold, silver, and more recently Bitcoin**
- **Cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin** are emerging as accepted hard currencies because they are widely accepted and limited in supply
- The biggest risk to money becoming an ineffective storehold of wealth is that a lot of it will be created — those who can create money always do
- In the early part of the Big Debt Cycle: a) money is typically hard and paper money circulates convertible into "hard money" at a fixed price, and b) there isn't a lot of paper money and debt outstanding

#### The Big Debt Cycle as Ponzi Scheme

- The cycle consists of building up **"paper money"** and debt assets/liabilities relative to **"hard money"** and real assets (goods and services) and relative to the income required to service the debt
- Works like a **Ponzi scheme or musical chairs** — investors hold increasing amounts of debt assets believing they can convert them into money with buying power, yet as debt assets increase relative to real things, conversion becomes more obviously impossible until realized and the process of selling the debt to get hard money begins

#### Debt Metrics in Sound Money Stage

- At early stage, private and government debt and debt service ratios are **low relative to incomes** and/or **low relative to liquid assets**
- Example: government debt and debt service are low relative to government tax revenue and/or low relative to government liquid assets (reserves, sovereign wealth assets)
- **US 1945 example**: ratios of US government debt and US money supply divided by gold were 7x and 1.3x respectively; now these ratios are 37x and 6x respectively

#### Economic Characteristics

- Debt levels, debt growth, economic growth, and inflation are **neither too hot nor too cold** — finances are sound
- **"Risky assets" relatively inexpensive** compared to "safe" assets due to memories of prior damage affecting psychology and pricing
- Example: late 1940s and early 1950s stock earnings yields were roughly **4x that of bond yields**
- Healthy economy and good investment returns lead to the next stage

### Stage 2: The Debt Bubble Stage

**When debt and investment growth are greater than can be serviced from the incomes being produced.**

#### Bubble Characteristics

- Money is readily available and cheap
- **Debt-financed economic expansion** and economic boom
- Demands for and prices of goods, services, and investment assets driven up by debt-financed buying
- Sentiment is very bullish
- By most conventional measures, the market is **overpriced**

#### Investor Psychology

- Amazing new inventions that are truly transformative
- Investors invest **without ability or care to assess whether present value of future cash flows will be greater or less than their costs**

> **"There is always a current most popular meme that just about everyone believes. It is reflected in the price and is bound to be wrong in some way. These memes typically are due to a mix of extrapolating what happened before and emotional considerations. Also, most investors typically don't take into consideration market pricing. In other words, they tend to identify what has been a great investment (e.g., a strongly performing company) as great, and they don't pay enough attention to its pricing, even though its pricing (whether it is cheap or expensive) is the most important thing. At this time, it is typical for almost everyone to be looking to make money by buying assets that they believe will go up (rather betting on them going down), and they quite often use leverage."**

#### Debt Growth Dynamics

- Dynamic eventually produces a bubble — **rates of debt and debt service growth to finance speculation being greater than income growth rates** needed to service the debts
- Markets and economies seem great, most everyone believes they will get better, financed by lots of borrowing, and **"wealth" is created out of nothing**
- "Wealth created out of nothing" = greater imagined wealth versus actual existing wealth
- Bubble periods identifiable by: extensive periods of debt growth (3+ years) significantly faster than income growth, high asset prices relative to traditional present value measures, and many other factors measured in **bubble indicator** (see economicprinciples.org and Principles In Action app)
- Contemporary example: **unicorn company valued at over $1 billion** that made owner a "billionaire" on paper but only raised $50 million in capital because speculative venture capitalists put in money to get option-like chips

#### The Debt Spiral

- Eventually debt spiral reaches and goes beyond **the point of no return** — debt and debt service levels go beyond those that can be prevented from accelerating without great losses to debt investors
- Self-reinforcing **debt "death spiral"** occurs when there is a need to borrow to service debt at a time when interest rates are rising because risks of holding debt/currency have become apparent
- This leads to a debt crisis

### Stage 3: The Top Stage

**When the bubble pops and there is a debt/credit/market/economic contraction.**

- Popping typically occurs due to combination of **tightening of money** and prior rate of debt growth being unsustainable
- When bubble pops, self-reinforcing contraction begins — debt problems **spread very quickly, like an aggressive cancer**
- Very important for policy makers to deal with it quickly — either to reverse it or guide the deleveraging to its conclusion

#### Policy Response

- In most cases, debt contraction can be **temporarily reversed by giving the system a heavy dose of what caused the debt problem** — creating more credit and debt
- Continues until it can't continue anymore, at which time a big deleveraging occurs

### Stage 4: The Deleveraging Stage

**When there is a painful bringing down of debt and debt service levels to be in line with income levels so that the debt levels are sustainable.**

#### Debt Crisis Spreads from Private to Public Sector

- At the beginning of the last stage when there is a big debt crisis, debt problems typically **spread from private sector to central government and then to central bank**

> **"Net selling of debt assets, especially net selling of government debt assets, is a big red flag."**

- When that happens, conditions deteriorate quickly unless managed very well and very quickly by central governments and central banks
- Private holders of debt sell the debt fearing bad returns
- Selling takes the form of **"runs on banks"** — turning-in of debt assets to get real money, which lenders/banks don't have enough of

#### The Death Spiral Dynamic

- When debt problems become apparent and holders sell debt assets, that initially **drives interest rates on the debt up**
- Makes debt more difficult to service, hence more risky, which drives interest rates higher
- Central bank typically provides money and credit to fill in for inadequate demand, which **reduces the value of money and credit** and reduces credit risk
- Selling of government's debt leads to: a) free-market-driven tightening of money and credit, b) weakening of the economy, c) downward pressure on the currency, and d) declining reserves as central bank attempts to defend the currency

#### The Vicious Cycle

- Classically, these runs accelerate and feed on themselves as holders of debt assets see that they will lose buying power (through default or devaluation of money)
- Causes **great shifts in market values and wealth** until debts are defaulted on, restructured, and/or monetized
- Because tightening proves too harmful for economy, central bank eventually simultaneously eases credit and allows devaluation of the currency
- Devaluation of money can itself be reason to sell debt asset because it becomes poor storehold of wealth
- Creates what is called a debt **"death spiral"** — self-reinforcing, debt-contraction dynamic where rising interest rates cause problems that creditors see, leading them to sell debt assets, which leads to even higher interest rates or need to print more money, which devalues money and leads to even more selling

#### Spending Cuts Paradox

- When this happens to government debt, realization that too much debt is the problem naturally leads to **inclination to cut spending and borrowing**
- However, because **one person's spending is another person's income**, cutting spending typically only contributes to increases in debt-to-income ratios
- Typically when policies are shifted to a mix of **debt restructurings and debt monetizations**, with mix chosen primarily dependent on how much of the debt is denominated in the country's currency

#### Movement to Equilibrium

- This defaulting on, restructuring of, and/or monetizing of debt **reduces debt burdens relative to incomes** until a new equilibrium is reached
- Movement to stable equilibrium typically takes place via a **few painful adjustment spasms** because borderline financial soundness is achieved before secure financial soundness

### Stage 5: The Deleveraging Process

#### Classic Deleveraging Progression

- Early in recession/depression phase, central banks bring interest rates down and make credit more available
- However, when: a) debts are large and debt contraction is underway, b) interest rates can't be lowered any more (e.g., when they fall to around 0%), c) there is not enough demand for government debt, and d) monetary easing is not enough to offset the self-reinforcing depressionary pressures — **central bank is forced to switch to new "tools"** to stimulate the economy

#### The Zero Lower Bound Problem

- Classically, to stimulate the economy the central bank must lower interest rates to below nominal economic growth rates, inflation rates, and bond rates, but that is **difficult to do when they approach 0%**
- At same time, central government is typically getting itself into a lot more debt because **tax revenues are down** and spending is up to support the private sector
- Yet there is not enough private sector demand to buy that debt
- Central government experiences a **debt squeeze** — free-market demand for its debt falls short of the supply of it
- If there is net selling of the debt, that creates a much worse problem

#### "Pushing on a String"

- Often in this deleveraging stage, there is a **"pushing on a string"** — phrase coined by policy makers in the 1930s
- Occurs late in long-term debt cycle when central bankers struggle to convert their stimulative policies into increased spending
- Because savers, investors, and businesses fear borrowing and spending and/or there is deflation, the risk-free interest rate they are getting is **relatively attractive to them**
- Difficult to get people to stop saving in **"cash"** even when interest rates go to 0% (or even below 0%)
- Phase is characterized by economy entering a **deflationary, weak, or negative growth period** as people and investors hoard low-risk, typically government-guaranteed cash

#### The Central Bank's Dilemma

- At this stage, central banks must choose between keeping money **"hard"** (which will lead debtors to default on their debts, leading to deflationary depressions) or making money **"soft"** by printing a lot of it, which will devalue both it and the debt
- Because paying off debt with hard money causes such severe market and economic downturns, when faced with this choice **central banks always eventually choose to print and devalue money**
- Of course, each country's central bank can only print that country's money

#### Printing and Devaluation

- At this stage, if it has ability to "print money," the central bank creates a substantial amount of money and credit and **throws it aggressively at the markets**
- Typically buys government debt and private sector debt of systemically important entities at risk of defaulting (to make up for private sector inadequate demand for debt and to keep interest rates artificially low)
- Sometimes buys equities and creates incentives for people to buy goods, services, and financial assets
- Also typically desirable to **devalue the currency** because that is stimulative to the economy and raises inflation rates, thus negating the deflationary pressures
- If currency is linked to gold, silver, or something else, that link is typically broken and there is a **move to a fiat monetary system**
- If currency isn't linked (i.e., if currency is already a fiat currency), devaluing it relative to other storeholds of wealth and other currencies is helpful

#### Interest Rate Dynamics

- In some cases, central bank's moves can drive nominal interest rates higher — either because central bank tightens monetary policy to fight inflation or because it doesn't tighten money to fight inflation and holders of debt don't want to buy newly issued government debt and/or they want to sell it because it doesn't provide an adequate return
- Important to **watch real and nominal interest rates and the supply and demand for debt** to understand what is happening

#### Extraordinary Measures

- At such times, **extraordinary policies to get money** like imposing extraordinary taxes and capital controls become common
- Governments will adopt policies that would have previously seemed unimaginable, such as **selectively freezing or seizing the assets of "enemy" countries or creating new forms of money**
- Note: not saying these extraordinary measures always happen; only saying it is wise to carefully consider the possibility that they will happen

#### Beautiful Deleveraging

- Deleveraging stage is typically a **painful time when debt burdens are reduced by defaults, restructurings, and/or devaluations**
- When an aggressive mix of debt restructurings and debt monetizations inevitably takes place to reduce debt and debt service burdens relative to incomes
- In typical deleveraging, debt-to-income ratio has to be lowered by roughly **50%, give or take about 20%**
- Can be done well or poorly
- When done well — what is called a **"beautiful deleveraging"** — central governments and central banks simultaneously do both debt restructurings and monetary stimulations in a balanced way
- Restructurings reduce debt burdens and are deflationary
- Monetary stimulations also reduce debt burdens (by providing money and credit to make it easier to buy debt) but are **inflationary and stimulative to the economy**
- If they get the balance right, positive growth occurs with falling debt burdens and acceptable inflation
- Whether done well or poorly, this is the stage of the Big Debt Cycle that **reduces a lot of the debt burden and establishes the bottom** that can be built on to begin the next Big Debt Cycle

### Stage 6: The Big Debt Crisis Recedes

**When a new equilibrium is reached, and a new cycle begins.**

#### Requirements for Viable System

**In order to have a viable debt/credit/money system, it is imperative that:**
- **a) debt/money is sound enough to be a viable storehold of wealth**
- **b) debt and debt service burdens are in line with the incomes to service them so that debt growth is sustainable**
- **c) creditors and debtors both believe that those things will exist**
- **d) the availability of money and credit and real interest rates begin to fall in line with that which is needed by both lender-creditors and borrower-debtors**

- Movement toward these things happening in the late phase of the Big Debt Cycle
- Requires both **psychological and fundamental adjustments**
- After a big deleveraging, it is typically difficult to convince lender-creditors to lend because the devaluations/restructurings they experienced in the deleveraging make them risk-averse

#### Credibility-Restoring Actions

- Imperative that central government and central bank take **credibility-restoring actions**
- Generally involve bringing their finances in order by: a) central government earning more money than it spends, and/or b) central bank making money hard again by offering high real yields, raising reserves, and/or linking the currency to something hard like gold or a strong currency
- Typically, in this stage, **interest rates need to be relatively high** in relation to inflation rates and more than high enough to compensate for currency weakness
- So it **pays to be a lender and is costly to be a borrower**
- This stage of the cycle can be **very attractive for lender-creditors**

## Chapter 1: Concluding Observations

### A Few Concluding Observations

#### Big Debt Crises Are Inevitable

> **"Big debt crises are inevitable."**

- Throughout history only very few well-disciplined countries have avoided them
- Inevitable because **lending is never done perfectly** relative to incomes needed to service it
- Often done badly because people always want more credit and that turns into debt
- Debt levels get beyond that which is sustainable, which leads to need to bring debt burdens down
- Typically leads to mixture of **debt defaults/restructurings and the creating of money and credit**, causing debt crisis to occur
- People's psychology reinforces the cycle: bubble period makes people more optimistic (causing them to borrow more), and bust causes people to be more pessimistic (causing them to cut spending)
- Even though this progression has happened many times in history, most policy makers and investors think their current circumstances and monetary system won't change — **the change is unthinkable — and then it happens suddenly**

#### Savings Matter

> **"It pays to build up savings in the good times so there are savings to draw on in the bad times. There are costs to having too much savings as well as too little savings, and no one gets the balance exactly right."**

#### Focus on Interrelated Dynamics

> **"The best way to anticipate a debt crisis happening is not by focusing on a single influence or number like debt as a percent of GDP; it is by understanding and focusing on a number of interrelated dynamics."**

- Will get into especially in the next two chapters

#### Currency Control and Money Printing

> **"If debts are denominated in a country's own currency, its central bank can and will 'print' the money to alleviate the debt crisis."**

- Allows central bank to manage the crisis better than if the central bank can't print the money
- But of course it also reduces the value of the money
- If debt is not denominated in a currency that the central bank can print, then it will have **debt defaults and deflationary depressions** measured in the currency that it owes and can't print

#### Managing Debt Crises Through Policy Mix

> **"All debt crises, even big ones, can be managed well by economic policy makers restructuring and monetizing the debt so that the deflationary ways of reducing the debt burdens (i.e., writing off and restructuring debt) and the inflationary ways of reducing debt burdens (i.e., creating money and credit and giving it to the debtors to make it easier for them to service their debts) balance each other. The key is to spread the paying back over time."**

- For example, if debt-to-income ratio needs to fall by about 50% to make it sustainable, a debt restructuring that spreads it out at a rate of 3% or 4% per year would be **much less traumatic** than one that is about 50% in one year

#### Opportunities in Crises

> **"Debt crises provide great risks and opportunities that have been shown to both destroy empires and provide great investment opportunities for investors if they understand how they work and have good principles for navigating them well."**

#### Need Long-Term Perspective

> **"If you try to focus on debt cycles precisely or focus your attention on the short term you won't see them."**

- It's like comparing two snowflakes and missing that they are pretty much the same because they're not exactly the same

**That's it in a nutshell.**

#### Preview of Rest of Study

- In rest of study, will get into the mechanics in greater depth
- Show the actual sequences that have played out over 35 cases
- Look at how the Big Debt Cycle and Overall Big Cycle that includes other big cycles (cycles of internal and external order) that started in 1945 and that we are currently in the late stages of have transpired relative to this template
- Briefly look at Chinese and Japanese Big Cycles and a number of other cases
- **Japanese case** is interesting because Japan is further along in its Big Debt Cycle — notably, its large debt and debt monetizations have led to depreciation of its currency and debt, which has led holders of its bonds to have **losses of 45% relative to holding US dollar debt since 2013** and **losses of 60% relative to holding gold since 2013**

**In the final chapters, I will share how I am processing the US relative to this template, how the US could reduce the risk of an acute debt crisis, and how I see the rough outline of future events unfolding.**

