## Chapter 2: The Mechanics in Words and Concepts

### How the Machine Works

**Everything changes like a perpetual motion machine. To understand this machine, one needs to understand its mechanics, and because everything affects everything else, these mechanics are very complex.**

- As a result of breakthroughs in artificial intelligence, we may be on brink of almost understanding it all
- For now, we have to labor along the old-fashioned way, with people studying what happened using contemporary computers
- This is how author created description of mechanics of debt/credit/money/economic dynamic

#### The Five Most Important Drivers of Change

> **"The five most important drivers of change that are important to understand are:"**

- **The debt/credit/money/economic cycle**
- **The internal political order/disorder cycle**
- **The external geopolitical order/disorder cycle**
- **Acts of nature (droughts, floods, and pandemics)**
- **Human inventiveness, most importantly of new technologies**

- These are the biggest forces that affect each other to shape the biggest things that happen
- Will go into these forces in more detail in Chapter 8
- Reference: can read about them in book *Principles for Dealing with the Changing World Order*

#### Focus on Debt/Credit/Money/Economic Dynamic

**In this study, we are going to examine the first of those — the debt/credit/money/economic dynamic — focusing most intensely on the late part of the long-term debt cycle when central governments and central banks "go broke."**

- Will walk through some mechanics of how market prices are determined
- Then look at how the long-term debt cycle works
- Will turn to the archetypical sequence that leads to a country hitting the limits of debt and money and central governments and central banks going broke
- At same time, will explore the other four forces because the interactions of these five forces cannot be overlooked in observing the resulting Overall Big Cycle
- From what can be seen, we are likely entering the **very turbulent stage in the Overall Big Cycle** driven by the interactions of these five big forces
- Resulting changes in world order will be big
- Hope this study can contribute to better understanding of the dynamics and better decision making to produce the best outcomes possible

### Money and Credit Are the Lifeblood of the Economy

**To me, money and credit are the lifeblood of the economy. They circulate nutrients (i.e., spending power) from the parts of the system that have excess amounts of the power to the parts of the system that can best use it. The central government is like the brain that directs how the system works while also taking in and using some of the money and credit (typically about 15-30% of it) to perform its functions (e.g., providing for social programs, defense, etc.). The central bank is like the heart that produces and pumps money and credit through the system. If the exchanges go well, and those who get capital use it productively, then the providers of capital, the users of it, and the economic system as a whole all prosper. If they don't, the system will become ill and experience trauma.**

#### Debt Dynamic as Perpetual Motion Machine

**To be clear, viewing the debt dynamic as a cyclical, perpetual motion machine working in essentially the same way through time and across countries doesn't mean that there are not changes over time and differences between countries.**

- Just that these changes are comparatively unimportant in relation to the timeless and universal mechanics and principles that are far less well understood than they should be
- To author, it's invaluable to first see these timeless and universal principles of how the machine works and then focus on the differences and what they are due to
- This approach provides a richer understanding of the cause/effect relationships
- Will start with these most important timeless and universal mechanics and principles
- To convey them in brief, will explain just the major ones in a big-picture, simplified way rather than detailed and precise way

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

### Price Determination Framework

- **Price formula**: Price = Total Spending ($) / Total Quantity Sold (Q)
- Understanding motivations of major buyers and sellers is key to price prediction
- Dalio's approach differs from conventional economics: focuses on **amount spent** rather than quantity bought
- Traditional economics measures demand/supply in quantity terms; this approach tracks dollar flows
- Conventional view assumes constant price elasticity across time; Dalio's framework shows elasticity varies with market participant motivations
- Price changes when rates of spending and/or quantities sold change
- Example: if buying rate drops from X to (X - 10%), price falls 10%

> "By identifying rates of unsustainable buying and/or rates of unsustainable selling you can identify unsustainable prices and unsustainable economic conditions."

- Can calculate what return to normal buying/selling looks like and predict price changes
- Dalio discovered this approach in 1970s analyzing livestock, grain, oilseed prices; extended to financial assets and entire economies

### Debt Dynamics vs. Conventional Psychology

- Most people mistakenly view debt busts and depressions as primarily psychological
- Dalio showed policymakers before 2008 US crisis and 2010-12 Europe crisis that debt buying would slow because:
  - Financial institutions were leveraging up balance sheets
  - Would hit regulatory leverage limits
  - Pace of buying would slow as supply of debt to sell increased
  - Less buying + more selling = crisis ahead
- Policymakers ignored supply-demand calculations, assumed confidence would sustain buying
- Policy makers often say: "If we control budget deficits in out-years, investors will have confidence and bond market will be fine"
- This is naive—fails to look at bond buyer motivations and calculate who will buy/sell what amounts

### Money Creation and Economic Growth

**When a) more money/credit created (more spending) and b) producers have capacity to produce more quantity, then c) non-inflationary growth occurs** (both $ and Q increase)

**But when a) more money/credit created (more spending) and b) little/no capacity so producers can't produce much more, then c) little real growth and much more inflation**

- Early cycle (excess capacity, stimulative central banks): strong growth, little inflation
- Late cycle: weak growth, big price rises
- **High productivity growth allows non-inflationary growth to continue longer** as producers can increase Q as $ increases
- Productivity can show up as quality improvements or marginal costs falling to zero (e.g., photos, electronic books)

### Why People Buy and Sell

**People buy goods/services to use and buy investments to make money (as storeholds of wealth)**

- Spending depends on: cost of goods/services relative to money/credit available, and relative appeal of spending on goods/services vs. financial assets
- **What people spend money/credit on is based on relative appeal of items**
- Two dimensions of comparison: 1) one item vs. another (stocks vs. bonds, beef vs. chicken, one currency vs. another vs. gold) and 2) same item at different delivery times (spot vs. future)
- **Arbitrages and relatively sure bets are most powerful determinants of relative pricing**

### Currency and Debt Relationship

- **Currencies are mediums of exchange and storeholds of wealth (in debt assets)** — facilitate both transactions and investing
- **Investments are exchanges of money/credit today for money/credit in future**
- **All investment markets derive value through yields and price changes; total return = yield + price change**
- **By and large, all investment markets compete with each other on basis of total returns** because: a) most investors care more about total returns than yield vs. appreciation and b) ability to arbitrage investments based on total returns

### Gold vs. Bonds Example

- Gold has no yield; US Treasury bond yields X% (e.g., 5%)
- Illogical to buy gold unless price expected to rise by more than X% per year (e.g., 5% per year)
- Market prices gold to rise 5% relative to Treasuries
- Investors form views on gold price drivers (e.g., inflation from money/credit creation)
- Compare 5% bond yield with expected gold appreciation from currency depreciation
- Simple price analysis plus financial engineering (e.g., leveraging, hedging) creates matrix of relative-value bets and arbitrages

### Real vs. Nominal Returns

- **Expected real returns of investments (relative to inflation) influence how much money goes into each**
- Real returns matter more than nominal because: a) investments are storeholds of wealth so buying power matters, and b) arbitrages between real assets and financial assets drive relative prices
- Expected returns of financial investments compared with expected returns of real assets (real estate, precious metals, commodities, art, etc.)
- Government bond returns (well-known yield, virtually no default risk in own currency) compared with inflation rate
- When bond yields low relative to inflation: bonds sold, inflation assets bought, and vice versa
- Central bank money/credit creation causes prices of goods, services, and most financial assets to rise → investors favor inflation-hedge assets

### Understanding Relative Pricing

- **Prices linked by determinants that must be understood to grasp relative pricing**
- Professional investors consider spot price (delivery today) and forward/futures prices (delivery in future)
- Arbitrages and relative-value bets determine price relationships at different delivery dates
- Same analysis for financial assets: short-term vs. long-term government debt (big factor: projected pace of central bank interest rate changes)

## DEBT IS CURRENCY AND CURRENCY IS DEBT

- **Since debt asset is promise to receive specified amount of currency at future date, debt and currency are essentially the same thing**
- **If you don't like the currency, you must not like the debt asset (e.g., bonds), and if you don't like the bonds, you must not like the currency, if you take into consideration their relative yields** (if you don't like one you must not like the other)
- Gold/bond comparison: relative yields + expected price changes = relative total returns
- Sets spot and futures prices for bonds and gold
- Same assessment drives value of different currencies and different debt assets of different countries
- Drives capital flows relevant to debt issues

### Currency Arbitrage Mechanics

- Government interest rate differences between countries drive currency expectations
- If Country A interest rate is X% lower than Country B's, expected currency appreciation in Country A must match the percentage rate
- Otherwise, virtually risk-free profits possible (owning bonds with higher interest rate)
- Interest rate difference expected to be eaten up by higher-interest-rate currency falling vs. lower-interest-rate currency

**Example scenario**: 10-year rate in Country A is 3% lower than Country B's

- Ordinarily expect Country A's currency to rise (to offset interest rate difference)
- But if Country A's currency expected to fall 2% per year instead: virtually risk-free profit opportunity
- Investors flock to trade, selling lower-yielding debt/currency
- Produces one of two adjustments (or combination):
  1. Spot currency must fall by 40% in this example, or
  2. 10-year interest rate must rise by 5%, sending bond prices down ~40%

- If adjustments can't happen (capital controls, etc.) and interest stays 3% less and currency falls 2%: loss compounds to 5% per year, totaling 40% over 10 years

**Country A's bond return will be very bad** if nominal returns aren't bad (bonds don't depreciate and debt burdens not reduced in nominal terms) because neither: a) bond prices fall in local currency (interest rates rise to provide appropriate return for declining currency) nor b) currency declines to make it cheap enough to provide adequate price appreciation

- Annual interest rate and currency weakness won't compensate for inflation
- Bad return comes because c) annual interest rate and weakness in currency won't compensate for inflation

## THE MAJOR TYPES OF PLAYERS AND HOW THEY BEHAVE TO DRIVE WHAT HAPPENS

**Five major types of players that drive money and debt cycles:**

1. **Borrower-debtors** (private or government entities)
2. **Lender-creditors** (private or government entities)
3. **Banks** (intermediaries between lender-creditors and borrower-debtors)
4. **Central governments**
5. **Government-controlled central banks** (create money/credit in country's currency, influence cost of money/credit)

- **Debt/credit expansions only occur when both borrower-debtors and lender-creditors are willing** — deal must be good for both
- One person's debts are another's assets; system requires both parties to want to transact
- **What's good for one is often bad for the other**
- For borrower-debtors: interest rates can't be too high or they must slash spending/sell assets to service debts or default
- For lender-creditors: interest rates can't be too low or they won't lend and will sell debt assets, causing interest rates to rise or central banks to print money and buy debt to hold rates down
- **This money printing/debt buying creates inflation, causing contraction in wealth and economic activity**

### The Balance Between Good and Bad Environments

- **Environments shift between those good/bad for lender-creditors and borrower-debtors**
- **Critical for anyone in markets/economies to know how to tell the difference**
- Balancing act happens naturally; sometimes conditions make it impossible to achieve good balance
- Causes big debt, market, and economic risks
- Before describing risk-producing conditions, explaining other players' motivations and how they act on them

### Private Sector Banks

- **Banks are intermediaries between lender-creditors and borrower-debtors**; their motivations and operations matter
- For thousands of years, banks have tried to profit by borrowing money from some and lending to others, earning money on spread
- **How bubbles and crises are created: banks lend out more money than they have by repeatedly borrowing at cost lower than return from lending**
- Works well for society and profitable for banks when: those lent money use it productively enough to pay back loans, and those banks borrowed from don't want their money back in amounts greater than banks actually have
- **Debt crises happen when loans aren't adequately paid back or when banks' creditors want more money back than banks can give them**

> "Over the long run, debts can't rise faster than the incomes that are needed to service them, and interest rates can't be too high for borrower-debtors or too low for lender-creditors for very long."

- If debts keep rising faster than incomes and/or interest rates too high for borrower-debtors or too low for lender-creditors too long: imbalance causes big market and economic crisis
- Pay attention to these ratios

### Big Debt Crises

- **Big debt crises occur when amounts of debt assets and debt liabilities become too large relative to amount of money in existence and/or amounts of goods and services in existence**

### Central Banks' Role

- **Central banks either directly or indirectly create money and credit, which is buying power**
- **Buying power determines total amount of spending on goods, services, and investment assets**
- Amount of money/credit created determines total amount of spending on goods, services, and financial assets (i.e., investments)
- **Total amount of money and credit created determines total amount of spending on goods, services, and financial assets**
- Goods, services, and financial assets tend to rise and decline with ebb and flow of money and credit, like boats rise and fall with sea
- **What this money/credit goes into and quantities of goods/services/financial assets produced are mostly determined by choices made by thousands or millions of market participants**

### Origins and Functions of Central Banks

- **Central banks came into existence to smooth these cycles, most importantly by handling big debt crises**
- Until recently (e.g., 1913 in US), most countries didn't have central banks
- Money in private banks was typically physical gold/silver or paper certificates to get gold/silver
- Throughout those times: boom/bust cycles because borrower-debtors, lender-creditors, and banks went through debt/credit cycles
- **These cycles turned into big debt and economic busts when too many debt assets and liabilities led to lender-creditor "runs" to get money from borrower-debtors, most importantly the banks**
- **These runs produced debt/market/economic collapses that eventually led governments to create central banks to lend money to banks and others when big debt crises happened**
- **Central banks can smooth cycles by varying interest rates and amount of money/credit in system to change behaviors of borrower-debtors and lender-creditors**

Where do central banks get their money? They "print" it (physically and digitally), which in large amounts alleviates debt problems by providing money/credit to those who need it but wouldn't otherwise have it. But doing so reduces buying power of money and debt assets and raises inflation.

- **Central banks want to keep debt and economic growth and inflation at acceptable levels** — don't want debt and demand to grow much faster or slower than is sustainable and don't want inflation too high or too low to be harmful
- Influence these by raising/lowering interest rates and tightening/easing money availability
- Influences lender-creditors and borrower-debtors striving to be profitable

### Central Governments' Role

- **Central governments are political organizations with those who run them serving at pleasure of elected officials who are elected by people, so they want to give people what they want**
- Typically done without paying for it → central government borrowing
- Reinforces cycle: greater credit stimulation early, debt depressants later
- When central governments do jobs well: tax and spend in ways providing broad-based productivity and prosperity, sometimes borrowing more than earning and sometimes paying it back
- When central banks do jobs well: keep credit, debt, and capital markets in relative balance, producing less disruptive big swings
- However, bias to create more ups in economies and markets through credit stimulation leads to long-term uptrends in debt and debt service relative to incomes until they become too large a percentage of income to be sustainable

> "The greater the size of the debt assets and debt liabilities relative to the real incomes being produced, the more difficult is the balancing act of having interest rates high enough to satisfy lender-creditors without having them be so high that they will hurt borrower-debtors, so the greater the likelihood of a debt-caused downturn in the markets and economy."

- **Because borrower-debtors, lender-creditors, banks, central governments, and central banks are the biggest players and drivers of these cycles, and because they each have obvious incentives affecting their behaviors, it is pretty easy to anticipate what they are likely to do and what is likely to happen next**

### The Predictable Cycle

**When debt growth is slow, economies are weak, and inflation is low**: central bankers will lower interest rates and create more money and credit, which will incentivize more borrowing and spending on goods, services, and investment assets, which will drive the markets for these things and the economy up. **At such times, it is good to be a borrower-debtor and bad to be a lender-creditor.**

**When debt growth and economic growth are unsustainably fast and inflation is unacceptably high**: central bankers will raise interest rates and limit money and credit, which will incentivize more saving and less spending on goods, services, and investment assets. **This will drive the markets and economy down because it's then better to be a lender-creditor-saver than a borrower-debtor-spender.**

- This dynamic leads to two interrelated cycles:
  - Short-term cycle: averaged ~6 years in length, give or take 3 years
  - Long-term cycle: averaged ~80 years, give or take 25 years
- Both evolve around upward trend line in productivity due to humanity's inventiveness

## THE SHORT- AND LONG-TERM (BIG) DEBT CYCLES

### Short-Term Debt Cycle

**By "short-term debt cycle"**: cycle of 1) recessions leading to 2) central banks providing credit cheaply, creating debt that initially leads to 3) market and economic booms, leading to 4) bubbles and inflations, leading to 5) central bankers tightening credit, leading to 6) market and economic weakening

- Typically lasts ~6 years, give or take ~3 years
- As of March 2025: 12 complete cycles in US since 1945, about two-thirds through the 13th
- **Each short-term debt cycle typically ends with higher levels of debt than the previous cycle because policy makers try to end recessions by lowering interest rates enough to get borrowing going again**

### Long-Term (Big) Debt Cycle

**By "long-term (big) debt cycle"**: cycle of building up debt assets and debt liabilities over long periods (i.e., successive short-term debt cycles) to amounts that eventually become unmanageable. This leads to combination of big debt restructurings and big debt monetizations that produce period of big market and economic turbulence.

- **Short-term debt cycles add up to the long-term (big) debt cycle, which I call the Big Debt Cycle**

### The Upward-Sloping Productivity Trend

- **These cycles move markets and economies around an upward-sloping trend line of rising living standards due to people's inventiveness and increases in productivity that come from it**
- Upward slope in productivity primarily driven by inventiveness of practical people (e.g., entrepreneurs) given adequate resources (e.g., capital) who work well with others (coworkers, government officials, lawyers, etc.) to make productivity improvements

**Over short period (1-10 years)**: short-term debt cycle is dominant

**Over long period (10 years and beyond)**: long-term debt cycle and upward-sloping trend line in productivity have much bigger effects

### Sustainable vs. Unsustainable Debt Cycles

- **What separates sustainable debt cycle from unsustainable one is whether the debt creates sufficient income to pay for debt service**
- If incomes fail to grow as quickly as debt and debt service, the ratio of debts to incomes will mechanically grow, requiring increased borrowing to service debt as well as to spend
- Cycle goes from low to high to unsustainably high debt and debt service relative to incomes
- **A sure sign of moving toward debt crisis is when there is large and rising amount of borrowing being used to pay for debt service**

### Why Central Bankers Don't Prevent Debt Cycles

Four reasons why central bankers don't better contain debt to prevent dangerous levels:

1. Most everyone, including central bankers, wants markets and economy to go up because that's rewarding and they don't worry about pain of paying back debts, so they push limits, becoming leveraged to long assets until debts become so burdensome they must be restructured to reduce relative to incomes
2. Not clear exactly what risky debt levels are because unclear what will happen to determine future incomes
3. Opportunity costs and risks to not providing credit that creates debt
4. Debt crises, even big ones, can usually be managed to reduce pain to acceptable levels

- **Debt isn't always bad, even when it's not economic** — too little debt/credit growth can create economic problems as bad or worse than too much, with costs coming as unrealized opportunities
- Because 1) credit can be used to create great improvements that aren't profitable that would have been forgone without it and 2) losses from debt problems can be spread out to not be intolerably painful if government in control of debt restructuring process and debt is in currency central bank can print
- However, to avoid debt crisis, debt must raise incomes enough to service the debt

> "Over time, from one cycle to the next, debt liabilities and debt assets have virtually always increased to produce the long-term debt cycle expansion. In virtually all cases, that has continued until the debt burdens have become unsustainably large or the debt assets have become intolerably low-returning."

### The Difficult Balancing Act

**When there are lots of debt assets and debt liabilities relative to incomes**: difficult for central bankers to keep interest rates high enough to satisfy lender-creditors without having them so high they unacceptably hurt borrower-debtors. Difficult for central banks to run monetary policy to balance growth and inflation well. **And because holders of debt assets want to sell the debt, one way or another debt is going to have a bad return. That puts central bankers in position of having to choose between:**

1. **Not printing money and buying debt (not monetizing debt)**: letting interest rates rise enough to cut credit demand and economic activity enough to reach indifference-equilibrium level that will balance buying and selling of bonds. This will make cash very valuable, devalue most other assets like stocks and hard assets, cause deflation, lead to debt defaults and restructurings, and depress economic activity. This typically happens first and is intolerable, which leads central banks to start...

2. **Printing money and buying debt (monetizing debt)** to make up for shortfall in demand, which will make money readily available and reduce its value thus raising inflation, raise value of most other assets like stocks and hard assets, minimize debt defaults, and stimulate economic activity. This typically happens eventually.

### Big Debt Crisis Periods

- At that part of Big Debt Cycle: need for big reductions in debt liabilities and debt assets
- These are big debt crisis periods
- Big debt restructurings and debt monetizations end prior Big Debt Cycle by reducing debt burdens and eliminating prior monetary order, leading to next Big Debt Cycle and monetary order
- Take place much like big changes in domestic political orders and big changes in world orders—like seismic shifts due to old order breaking down

**Four types of levers that policy makers can pull to reduce debt burdens:**

1. **Austerity** (spending less)
2. **Debt defaults/restructurings**
3. **Central bank "printing money" and making purchases (or providing guarantees)**
4. **Transfers of money and credit from those who have more than they need to those who have less**

### Why Austerity Fails

- Policy makers typically try austerity first because obvious and natural to want to let those who got themselves and others into trouble bear the costs
- This is big mistake — austerity doesn't bring debt and incomes back into balance
- Cutting debts cuts investors' assets and makes them "poorer," and because one person's spending is another person's income, cutting spending cuts incomes
- Cuts in debts and spending cause commensurate cut in net worths and incomes, which is very painful
- As economy contracts, government revenues typically fall at same time as demands on government increase → deficits increase
- Seeking to be fiscally responsible, governments tend to raise taxes, also a mistake because further squeezes people and companies

**When there is spending greater than revenues and liquid liabilities greater than liquid assets, that produces the need to borrow and sell debt assets**, which, if there's not enough demand, will produce one kind of crisis or another (either deflationary or inflationary).

### Beautiful Deleveraging

- **Best way for policy makers to reduce debt burdens without causing big economic crisis is to engineer what I call a beautiful deleveraging**
- **Beautiful deleveraging occurs when policy makers both: 1) restructure debts so debt service payments spread out over more time or disposed of (deflationary and depressing) and 2) have central banks print money and buy debt (inflationary and stimulating)**
- **Doing these two things in balanced amounts spreads out and reduces debt burdens and produces nominal economic growth (inflation plus real growth) that is greater than nominal interest rates, so debt burdens fall relative to incomes**

If done well: balance between deflationary and depressing reduction of debt payments and inflationary and stimulating printing of money and buying of debt by central banks. In countries Dalio studied, most big debt crises that occurred with debts denominated in country's own currency were restructured quickly, typically in 1-3 years. These restructuring periods are times of great risk and opportunity. More completely explained in *Principles for Navigating Big Debt Crises*.

## THE BIG DEBT CYCLE, ITS RISKS, AND HOW TO DEAL WITH IT NEED TO BE BETTER UNDERSTOOD

- **Because really big debt crises that take form of debt restructurings and devaluations come at ends of Big Debt Cycles happen roughly once in a lifetime, they are not well-understood relative to short-term cycles**
- Said differently: what ends long-term debt cycles is different from what ends short-term debt cycles
- Most people don't know about or acknowledge long-term debt cycles or worry about long-term debt cycles ending even though they're much bigger deals than short-term debt cycles ending
- It's dangerous — like eating fatty foods and having cholesterol accumulate in arteries and saying it doesn't seem to be causing trouble while increasing probability of heart attack

### What Is Healthy

Healthy debt: 1) private sector lenders give credit in exchange for debt that works well for them and creditors because uses of funds are profitable and 2) government borrowings used in ways producing productivity gains (e.g., investing in better infrastructure, education) that can be paid for via tax revenue, or for government to sometimes borrow and spend more than it takes in when economy needs stimulation and pay it back when conditions strong.

Unhealthy debt: 1) central bank chronically printing money and buying debt to make up for shortage in demand for debt and 2) central government chronically having large deficits that result in debt and debt service levels rising faster than incomes (in government's case, tax revenue) required to service them.

### Summary and Reiteration

- **Goods, services, and investment assets can be produced, bought, and sold with money and credit**

- **Central banks can produce money and can influence amount of credit in whatever quantities they want**

- **Borrower-debtors ultimately require enough money and low enough interest rates for them to be able to borrow and service their debts**

- **Lender-creditors require high enough interest rates and low enough default rates from borrower-debtors in order for them to get adequate returns to lend and be creditors**

- **This balancing act becomes progressively more difficult as sizes of debt assets and debt liabilities both increase relative to incomes. Eventually they need to be reduced, so a deleveraging happens**

- **Best type of deleveraging is what I call a beautiful deleveraging, which can be engineered by central governments and central banks to reduce debt burdens if debts are in their own currencies. If debts are denominated in foreign currency, the deleveraging is quite ugly. I will explain these later**

- **Over long term, being productive and having healthy income statements (i.e., earning more than one is spending) and healthy balance sheets (i.e., having more assets than liabilities) are markers of financial health**

- **If you know where in debt/credit cycle each country is and how players are likely to behave, you should be able to navigate these cycles well**

- **The past is prologue**

### Important Takeaways

- **Debt crises are inevitable** — throughout history only a very few well-disciplined countries have avoided debt crises because lending is never done perfectly and is often done poorly due to how cycle affects people's psychology to produce bubbles and busts

- **Most debt crises, even big ones, can be managed well if economic policy makers spread out their negative impacts**

- **All debt crises provide investment opportunities if investors understand how they work and have good principles for navigating them well**

- **Inevitably, at beginning of end of Big Debt Cycle when there is lot of debt, it is difficult to keep real interest rates high enough to satisfy lender-creditors without them being too high for borrower-debtors**, and central banks try to navigate between these choices. Typically during these times, both tight-money economic contraction and loose-money inflation occur, and only question is in what order. In any case, owning debt/currency of overly indebted governments at such times is bad investment.

- **Central banks have to choose between keeping money "hard," which will lead debtors to default on their debts, which will lead to deflationary depressions, and making money "soft" by printing a lot of it, which will devalue both it and the debt**. Because paying off debt with hard money causes such severe market and economic downturns, when faced with this choice central banks always choose to print and devalue money eventually. For case studies, see Part II of *Principles for Navigating Big Debt Crises*. Of course, each country's central bank can only print that country's money, which brings me to my next big point.

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Chapter 2: Interacting Forces (continued)

### The Big Five Forces That Drive Change

- **Ray Dalio** references his book *Principles for Dealing with the Changing World Order*, which identified 18 measures of major condition drivers
- **The Big Five forces** that explain nearly everything:
  1. **Debt/credit/money/markets/economic cycle**
  2. **Social and political order/disorder cycle within countries**
  3. **Peace and war cycle between countries**
  4. **Acts-of-nature shocks** (droughts, floods, pandemics)
  5. **Human inventiveness** (new technologies that boost productivity)
- These forces **reinforce each other** both upward and downward — financial crises raise odds of internal conflict; internal conflicts worsen financial conditions
- Together they create **Big Cycles** of ups/downs, peace/war, leading to major shifts in domestic and world orders
- Monitoring these forces (particularly the big five) reveals **evolutionary declines of great powers**: rising indebtedness + weakening monetary systems + declining quality of education/infrastructure/law/civility/government effectiveness

> "These big rises and declines are easy to see by monitoring the 18 forces (particularly the big five) that I have shared with you."

## Chapter 3: The Mechanics in Numbers and Equations

### Defining Unsustainable Debt

- **Unsustainable debt** = when money coming in < money going out, either because:
  - Savings decline, or
  - Borrowing increases until savings run out
- Think of money flow like **blood flow**; income statements and balance sheets are the reports that show it
- **Healthy condition**: income from earning ≥ spending + debt service
- Debt growth isn't necessarily bad if borrowed money → income rising faster than debt service rises (healthy leverage)
- **When debts grow faster than incomes**, it's like **plaque in arteries** — reduces income flow available for spending/saving due to increased debt service
- If money flow gets constrained too much = **default (economic equivalent of heart attack)**

### The Four Most Important Debt Risk Indicators

While Dalio tracks ~35 indicators, **four matter most**:

1. **Debts relative to income**
   - As debts grow relative to income, higher interest/rollover payments each year
   - Greater risk existing debt won't be rolled over by creditors
   - Creates higher debt service as % of income, reducing money for spending

2. **Debt service relative to income**
   - Total amount debtor must pay (interest + principal) to avoid default
   - As this ratio rises, investors expect credit problems and stop lending/sell existing debt assets
   - To estimate future debt service buildup, compare debt service interest rate to income growth rate

3. **Nominal interest rates relative to: a) inflation rates, b) nominal income growth rates (inflation + real growth)**
   - Shows how debt/debt service will grow relative to incomes
   - Example: 100% debt-to-income, 5% nominal interest, 3% nominal growth → next year owes ~102% of income
   - Shows how attractive credit conditions are for lenders vs. borrowers
   - High nominal rates relative to nominal growth = favorable for lenders, unfavorable for borrowers (encourages lending, discourages borrowing)
   - Low rates relative to growth = favorable for borrowers, unfavorable for lenders

4. **Debt and debt service relative to savings (reserves)**
   - Large savings cushion reduces default risk even if other metrics are unhealthy
   - Can draw down savings to make debt/spending payments

> "Inevitably, equilibrium levels of 1) debts relative to incomes, 2) debt service relative to incomes, 3) nominal interest rates relative to inflation (i.e., real interest rates) and nominal growth rates, and 4) debts and debt service relative to savings will be approached. If you watch these ratios over time, you will see them go to extreme levels and return to more normal levels one way or another. If you understand the cause/effect relationships that drive these changes, you can understand how to navigate them and how they can be best managed. Most importantly, if you understand the painful deleveraging part, you will understand that it can be handled well (to be less painful) or handled poorly (and be very painful)."

- Countries with **very high debt levels, large deficits, low savings, very high and fast-rising interest rates** = very high risk of debt default or devaluation crisis

### Mathematical Formulas for Debt Burdens

**1. Future debts relative to future income:**

```
Future Debt/Future Revenue =
[(Future Expenses Excluding Interest - Future Revenue) + Current Debt × (1 + Interest Rate)] /
[Current Revenue × (1 + Growth Rate)]
```

- Debt-to-revenue grows if: spending > revenue, compounding existing debts, or revenue growth lags
- Interest rates rising makes existing debts grow faster
- Revenue growth makes debt-to-revenue ratio fall
- **Focuses on debt-to-revenue, not debt-to-GDP** — GDP doesn't matter for government's debt service; actual cash flows matter

**2. Future debt service relative to future income:**

```
Future Debt Service/Future Revenue =
[(Future Interest Costs + Future Principal Payments)] / [Current Revenue × (1 + Growth Rate)]

Where:
Future Interest Costs = Future Debt Level × Average Effective Interest Rate on Debt
Future Principal Payments = Future Debt Level × Share of Debts Coming Due
```

- Interest rates rising gradually affects debt service over time as bonds "roll" (mature and get reissued at new rates)
- Principal payments = debt coming due each year, typically financed by issuing new debt
- When debtors are stressed, creditors shorten maturity, increasing principal payments at same debt level

**3. Interest rate required to keep debt flat:**

```
Interest Rate Required to Keep Debt Flat =
Revenue Growth Rate - [(Future Expenses Excluding Interest - Future Revenue) / Starting Debt Level]
```

- If primary deficit = 0, debts stay flat if interest rate = revenue growth rate
- If primary deficit = 5% of debt, interest rates need to be 5% below revenue growth rate
- If interest rates = revenue growth, debts compound at same rate income is growing
- If government also borrowing, debts compound slower than income, so interest rates must be below revenue growth
- As interest rates rise relative to revenue growth, debts grow relative to incomes (existing debts compound faster than revenue), and debt service grows even faster (both debt level grows AND interest rate rises)

**4. Debts and debt service relative to savings:**

Similar formulas to (1) and (2), but using savings instead of income as denominator.

- Large debts + large savings = less concerning because can pay debt service and principal from savings (creates buffer)
- Consistent deficits + negative expected surplus → debts/debt service grow quickly relative to savings

### Rules of Thumb

- **If nominal interest rates = nominal income growth and no primary deficit**, debts stay flat relative to income
- **If interest rates > income growth**, existing debt burdens increase
  - Example: 2% higher rates than growth for 20 years → debt-to-income increases ~50%
  - Starting at 50% debt → goes to 75%; starting at 400% → goes to 600%

> "Debt service expenses accumulating is like plaque in the arteries accumulating in that it squeezes out the desired flow of nutrients to the economy."

> "The main effect of high debt levels is making the debtor vulnerable to not being able to roll it forward."

### Example 1: US Debt Trajectory

- US government expenditures excluding interest projected to average ~112% of income over next decade
- **Primary deficit** (non-interest expenses - income) = ~12% of income
- US borrowing ~20% of income yearly to cover interest on existing debt
- Current US debt-to-income = ~580%
- **Projection**: Assuming interest rates = income growth, US debt-to-income will rise by ~120% over 10 years (580% → 700%), with proportional increase in interest expense and debt service burden
- Tables show that as starting debt level rises and deficits increase, expected debt level rises exponentially

**Key comparative debt levels (as of writing):**
| Country | Debt/GDP | Debt/Govt Revenue | Deficit (% Govt Revenue) | Revenue (% GDP) |
|---------|----------|-------------------|--------------------------|-----------------|
| USA | 100% | 583% | 37% (6% of GDP) | 17% |
| JPN | 215% | 1376% | 26% (4% of GDP) | 16% |
| CHN | 90% | 321% | 16% (5% of GDP) | 28% |
| FRA | 86% | 478% | 31% (6% of GDP) | 18% |
| DEU | 44% | 340% | 17% (2% of GDP) | 13% |
| GBR | 92% | 256% | 16% (6% of GDP) | 36% |

### Example 2: Interest Rate Differentials

- **When interest rates > income growth rates**, existing debt grows relative to incomes (debt compounds faster than incomes)
- Using CBO projections: US will average 3.45% effective interest rates, 3.9% nominal growth over next decade
- Difference = ~-0.4%, leaving US in manageable range
- Tables demonstrate: **as debts get higher, impact of high interest rates gets worse much faster**
- Even small interest rate disadvantages compound dramatically at high debt levels

### Example 3: Interest Rate Death Spiral

**Scenario**: Government with 580% debt-to-income, 3.9% nominal growth, 3.5% interest rates, 32% spending above income, 35% of debt maturing yearly

- Year 1: Must sell $12.2 trillion debt ($10.5 trillion rollover + $1 trillion interest + new borrowing)
- **If public unwilling to buy debt at current rates**, interest rates must rise until someone willing to buy
- Rising interest rates → more expensive borrowing → larger deficits → greater desire to sell bonds → even more upward pressure on rates

> "A spiral of rising interest rates leading to worsening credit risk, leading to less demand for the debt, leading to higher interest rates is a classic debt 'death spiral.'"

**Model showing 0.5%/year interest rate increase while nominal growth stays flat:**
- Year 10: Debts at 865% of income, interest at 67%, total debt service 342%
- **Rising interest rates make debts more unsustainable**, constricting income growth and challenging sustainability further

### Four Ways Governments Reduce Debt Burdens

1. **Austerity** (spending less) — doesn't work; one person's spending = another's earnings, causing self-reinforcing deflationary contraction
2. **Debt defaults/restructurings** — deflationary; one person's debts = another's assets
3. **Central bank printing money and buying debt** — reduces debt burdens by providing money to pay debts; inflationary
4. **Transfers from private market players with money to government via taxes**, then transferred to other private players

- Historical private debt crises show **mix of these levers**, with **strong bias toward printing money and buying debt (monetizing)**
- Fight over increased taxes common, with conflict between political left and right
- Central governments = largest part of economy, only part that can pay for large non-economic social expenses (critical when economic conditions bad)
- Slow government response creates larger economic downturn, worsening debt burdens by reducing income growth/net worth, potentially leading to social turmoil
- Self-damagingly painful for over-indebted governments to cut spending during debt problems

> "The easiest path, though not the best path for the long-term health of the system, is for governments to resolve their debt problems and spend as they would like to spend by having the central bank print money and purchase the bonds, thereby holding interest rates down at tolerable levels and putting money into the system. That is what they will unfailingly do when the debts are denominated in their own currencies."

### Example 4: Central Bank Intervention

**Scenario modification**: Instead of allowing interest rate spiral, central bank steps in to buy excess debt supply and maintain rates/liquidity at desired level

- Government needs to sell $12.2 trillion Year 1
- **Central bank buys all excess issuance** so private sector holds no more than 600% of government income in debt, keeping interest rates flat at 3.5%
- Year 2: Central bank must buy $0.1 trillion of debt assets
- As central bank prints more to cover shortfalls, **money supply balloons**

**Mechanically, to monetize government debt**, central bank:
- **Prints money** (creates new reserves/cash)
- Gives private players cash in exchange for bonds → increases money supply (M0)
- Example assumes money supply starts at $5.7 trillion (110% of government income) — roughly where US is today
- **As central bank prints more to cover government shortfalls, money supply balloons**

**Impact on currency:**
- All else equal, **central bank money creation lowers currency value and increases inflation/currency weakness**
- Lowering interest rates and increasing money supply reduces currency attractiveness
- **In following tables**: Shows how much money gets printed and currency impact based on:
  - Starting debt-to-income levels (rows)
  - Private sector willingness to hold government debt (columns)
- **As debt problems worsen and private sector becomes less willing to lend**, money stock increases more
- Example shows central bank buying $6 trillion bonds, increasing money stock from $5.7 trillion to $11.8 trillion

**Currency depreciation mechanics:**
- Lowering interest rates usually causes currency to sell off
- Lower 10-year forward currency doesn't change much with rate cuts
- But lower interest in meantime = worse deal, so spot currency must fall to make up for lost interest (reaching same expected 10-year forward point)
- Forward currency premium offset by present value interest rate differences (explained in Chapter 2)
- Printed money can flow out of currency, creating selling pressure
- As currency becomes more sensitive to money supply, expect greater currency weakness

**Tables show expected currency depreciation:**
- Printing 1% of GDP in money → expect ~10% currency depreciation at 5.8x starting debt-to-income with 600% max private bond holdings
- As currency becomes more sensitive to money amount (M0) and private sector less willing to lend → more currency weakness

### Policy Implications

- Given government's debt level and projected deficit, can calculate what interest rate needed to produce any specified debt/debt service level relative to incomes
- Can solve for: keeping debt burden same, having it decline, etc. — given estimates of future revenue and expenses
- For Fed: Would want to set interest rate so debt burdens don't become too great over time
- Example: What interest rate keeps debt service payments flat? This would affect interest rate policy

<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## Formula for Determining Future Debt Burdens

**Future Debt/Future Revenue** = (Future Expenses Excluding Interest - Future Revenue) + Current Debt × (1 + Interest Rate) / Current Revenue × (1 + Growth Rate)

### How the US Can Stabilize Debt-to-Income in Next 10 Years

Author applies formula to US case (central gov't debt 100% GDP, 583% revenue; projected 2035: 118% GDP, 648% revenue):

**Four single-lever scenarios to stabilize debt burdens:**
- **Interest rates drop to 1.0%** (from current 4.5%) — fall of 3.5%
- **Inflation rises to 4.5%** (from projected 2.0%) — increase of 2.5%
- **Spending cuts of 12%** (47% of discretionary spending)
- **Revenue increase of 11%** (raising taxes by 11%)

Each lever alone is "intolerably too large" — requires the right combination of lesser amounts. Author promises a "3% 3-Part Solution" in Chapter 18.

> "To protect Apollo's performance for all users, this endpoint has a display limit of 50,000 records."

