## PART III: LOOKING BACK

### Framework for Historical Analysis

**Two guiding principles for understanding big events**:

1. **Focus on big things, not small details**: People trying to see things up close typically miss the most important big things because they're preoccupied with precision. When looking for big things, pay attention to big things.

2. **Understand cause/effect relationships**: Everything happens for reasons that make it happen. Strive to understand and explain cause/effect relationships that drive changes and create a logical template/model that explains past changes and aligns with current reality. If discrepancies exist, work to understand and resolve them.

> "This timeless and universal template has been working in essentially the same way for thousands of years in all countries, driven by the same basic and logical cause/effect relationships."

### What's Coming in Part III

- Big Cycles transpire in analogous ways across countries and times
- **Chapter 9**: Very brief overview of 80-year Big Cycle before 1945
- **Following chapters**: Complete picture from end of WWII until March 2025
- Separate chapters covering same periods for China and Japan
- Demonstrates Big Cycle template playing out repeatedly
- Enables use of template to examine current conditions and future possibilities (Part IV)

## Chapter 9: From 1865 to 1945 in a Tiny Nutshell

### 1865-1918: Post-Civil War to WWI

**US Civil War aftermath (ending 1865)**:
- War over usual issues: who controls economic, political, social matters (slavery in this case)
- **Very costly, financed by unsustainable debt**: US government debt rose from 2% to 40% of GDP; interest payments consumed over half the budget
- Confederate states' debts defaulted after war
- Dollar linked to gold at $20.67/ounce at war's start
- During war: Government defaulted on promise to convert dollars to gold
- Printed unbacked paper money ("greenbacks") → value plunged
- Gold in new currency soared to ~$250/ounce
- Inflation rate in new currency rose to 80% in 1865

> "During times when there is too much debt relative to the quantity of money that is needed to service debts, the need to either increase the amount of money that exists and/or cut the amount of debt there is leads governments to break their promises and do some combination of a) raising the amount of money and credit, b) reducing the amount of debt (e.g., by restructuring it), and/or c) preventing the free-market ownership and movement of the hard money (e.g., gold). At such times, there is a run away from bad money to good money that the government wants to stop. This often leads to prohibiting good money from being freely held and freely moved."

**1870-1914: Second Industrial Revolution**:
- Devaluation, defaults, monetary stimulation reduced debt burdens relative to incomes
- Post-war period of great productivity and leveraging created next bubble and bust
- **Classic pattern**: Debt- and equity-financed technological investment booms → economic advances, big wealth/values gaps → bubbles and busts → great internal conflicts
- Simultaneous global conditions: Newly powerful countries challenged established powers and world order → eventually led to war

**Major technological advances**:
- **Railroads**: Opened and linked Western/Eastern US
- **Steel production**: Built bridges, skyscrapers, railroads
- **Electricity**: Thomas Edison's light bulb, revolutionary distribution improvements
- **Telephone**: Alexander Graham Bell's invention
- **Oil production**: Fueled these advances
- **Automobile**: Invention and broad distribution

> "The great new inventions that were turned into great new products made these who came up with them and commercialized them very rich. The rich were increasingly resented (they were then called 'robber barons') for their business tactics and their lavishness (this era was called the Gilded Age), which led to classic left/right class conflicts developing in the early 20th century."

**Monetary system constraints**:
- **No central bank**; dollar fixed to gold by commercial banks
- **When debt busts occurred**: No money printing to ease them → some busts were very big and long-lasting

**Major financial panics**:
- **Panic of 1873**: Start of Long Depression, lasting until 1896
- Similar debt-bust panics in 1893 and 1907
- Gold standard became major political issue
- **William Jennings Bryan**: "You shall not crucify mankind upon a cross of gold"

> "Eventually, the severity of these booms and busts, especially the Panic of 1907, prompted the government to create the Federal Reserve central banking system in 1913 in order to better manage monetary policy for dealing with these boom/bust cycles."

**1900-1914: Late Big Cycle symptoms emerge**:
- Over-indebtedness
- Internal political conflicts between rich business elites/capitalists (right) and low-earning workers/socialists/anarchists (left)
- **Capitalism versus Marxism**: Economic/ideological conflict in both US and Europe
- Many extremist followers on both sides willing to fight to death rather than compromise

**Political developments**:
- **US**: Move toward left with progressive Theodore Roosevelt becoming president after William McKinley assassinated by anarchist
- Anarchists assassinated several world leaders around this time
- **Europe**: Rising power of Germany and allies challenged UK and allies (especially France)
- **Asia**: Japan went to war with and defeated Russia, becoming leading imperial power
- World much less connected; foreign countries seemed farther away
- By early 20th century, world starting to come closer together; US increasingly became world power

**1914: Archduke Franz Ferdinand assassinated → World War I began**

### WWI and Its Consequences

> "I won't go into the blow-by-blow of it, but I will say that it led to the world order changing in the classic big and important ways previously described, including the emergence of the United States as the world's richest and largest creditor nation."

**US emergence as financial superpower**:
- Played big role in financing war and manufacturing/selling war goods
- Didn't have major spending or war destruction costs (entered war late)
- Other winners (UK, France) weakened and indebted by war
- Losers devastated

**Germany's debt burden**:
- Terribly indebted to war lenders (immediately defaulted)
- Indebted to winners through reparations
- Economy burdened until Hitler defaulted in 1933

**Russia's transformation**:
- WWI brought conflict between rich monarchy (wanting to keep wealth/privileges) and poor masses (angry, wanting more)
- Led to civil war and dramatic domestic order change to Marxist-communist
- Created Soviet Union in 1922 by taking over Ukraine, Belarus, and parts of
<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## Chapter 9 (continued): Historical Perspective on WWI to WWII

### Post-WWI Settlement and League of Nations

- **Japan** became the leading power in Asia after WWI, having allied with the victors
- 1918 pandemic followed the war's end
- Winners met to determine the new world order—world becoming more interconnected through advances in transportation and communications
- **WWI** was first truly global (vs. regional) war—raised question of world governance for first time
- **President Wilson** aspired to create orderly world governance replicating US-style representative system
- Led to formation of **League of Nations**, which failed to prevent the next major war
- World governance remains unsolved: "We still haven't figured out how world governance could advance beyond fighting to determine who gets what they want"

### The Roaring '20s and Great Depression (1918-1930)

- **1918-1930**: Classic period of peace, inventiveness, and productivity driven by entrepreneurs creating new products financed by **debt and equity investments/speculations** that produced wealth inequality and bubbles
- **Roaring '20s**: Rapid economic growth and technological innovation produced great productivity early on—incomes exceeded what was needed to fuel advances and provide good returns
- Major inventions converted to mass production: automobiles, airplanes, radios, televisions, talking movies, refrigerators, drugs, medications
- What started as productive lending and investment grew into a big bubble
- **1929**: Burst with debt defaults and stock market crash, followed by depression
- Debt/economic/stock market crash greatly impacted domestic politics, international geopolitics, and monetary/political/geopolitical orders

### FDR's Response and Debt Crisis Principle

> "During times when there is too much debt relative to the quantity of money that is needed to service debts, the need to either increase the amount of money that exists and/or cut the amount of debt there is leads governments to break their promises and do some combination of a) raising the amount of money and credit, b) reducing the amount of debt (e.g., by restructuring it), and/or c) preventing the free-market ownership and movement of the hard money (e.g., gold). At such times, there is a run away from bad money to good money that the government wants to stop. This often leads to prohibiting good money from being freely held and freely moved."

**FDR's Actions**:
- Outlawed private ownership of gold
- Defaulted on promise to allow holders of paper money to convert it to gold
- Changed official exchange rate from $1 for 1/20.67th ounce of gold to $1 for 1/35th ounce—**devaluing money by ~40%**
- Imposed strict foreign exchange controls preventing Americans from taking money abroad
- Restricted Americans' abilities to have foreign bank accounts

### Wave of Debt Restructurings (1865-1945)

Many countries went broke between 1865-1945—partial list of major debt events:

- US leaving gold standard during and after Civil War, devaluing money
- Several countries leaving gold standard and devaluing money in Great Depression (beyond US)
- **Weimar Germany** restructuring Treaty of Versailles debts
- **China and Russia** repudiating past debts
- **China** abandoning silver standard in favor of paper currency (1935)
- **Greece** debasing coinage, expelled from early European currency union (1908)

### Rise of Fascism and Autocracy (1920s-1930s)

- Classic pattern: hard right (fascists) vs. hard left (communists) fighting for control
- **1920s-1930s**: Several inefficiently run, conflict-ridden representative governments (**Spain, Italy, Japan, Germany**) turned to demagogic leaders and autocracies of the right (fascism) to bring order
- Parallel to current US and other countries experiencing rightist shift
- Turn toward rightist governments led to squaring-off against leftists
- Marked move away from multilateralism, breaking of agreements, rise of **strongman unilateralism**
- **Hitler** broke out of Treaty of Versailles by defaulting on German debt obligations
- **Germany and Japan** became nationalistic and expansionistic, seizing territories in Europe, Africa, and Asia (more detail on Japan in Chapter 16)
- Ascendant powers rose at expense of prior leading world powers—**UK, France, Netherlands**—overextended and unable to defend colonies

> "When countries are weak, opposing countries take advantage of their weaknesses to obtain gains."

- Dynamics set stage for increased conflict between nations, eventually leading to **WWII**
- Beginning of next world order after WWII—"the one we are now in the late stages of"

### Pre-WWII Developments

- Reference to author's *Principles for Dealing with the Changing World Order*
- Period leading to WWII employed all classic pre-war maneuvers: economic warfare, freezing of financial assets, military buildups
- War began with **Germany's attack on Poland (1939)** and **Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor (1941)**
- Usual war developments unfolded: conventional weapons, then secret development and usage of powerful new weapons winning the war
- Unconditional surrenders of losers led to meetings of winners establishing new monetary, internal political, and external geopolitical orders
- Spoils went to winning Allies, penalties to Axis powers per **Treaty of Versailles**
- Decisions reshaped world order with implications for decades to come

### Transition to Post-WWII Period

> "We will next look in greater detail at what happened after the end of World War II until my writing of this book in March 2025. While I will frame the evolution of the cycle in the context of the Big Debt Cycle, showing how the Big Debt Cycle went through its various monetary regimes, I will also show how it combined with the other four forces to shape the Overall Big Cycle."

