## Chapter 10: A Brief Review of the Big Debt Cycle from 1945 to Now

### Author's Perspective and Approach

- Born 1949, global macro investor for most of life—both experienced and studied the period
- Sharing personal descriptions to enrich picture and pass along lessons from painful mistakes (which stick in mind more than wins)
- Story of last 75+ years shows almost in-unison swings in five forces from one extreme to other
- Each decade more likely opposite than similar to decade before
- Key times: end of each decade when markets/psychology expected more of same—logical moments to bet against the crowd

### The Five Forces Interaction

- Post-WWII story puts events in context of **Big Debt Cycle**
- Other four forces also swung greatly, interacting with debt cycles to shape outcomes
- Forces flow like waves—sometimes small, sometimes big, sometimes reinforcing, sometimes negating, sometimes creating perfect storms

### Core Debt Cycle Principle (Restated)

> "Normally, when central banks want to be stimulative, they lower interest rates and/or create a lot more money and credit, which creates a lot more spending and debt. This stimulation both extends the expansion phase of the cycle and raises debt assets and liabilities relative to incomes, which makes the debt asset and debt liability balance more precarious. History shows us that when central banks can't lower interest rates anymore and want to be stimulative, they print money and buy debt, especially government debt. That gives debtors, most importantly governments, money and credit to prevent them from defaulting and allows them to continue to borrow in order to spend more than they are earning until the debt assets and liabilities become too great to balance, which is when a debt restructuring and/or debt monetization must occur."

### The Current Big Debt Cycle Overview

**US Experience 1945-2024**:
- **12 complete short-term debt cycles**, averaging ~6 years each
- About **two-thirds through the 13th cycle**
- Added up to **one Big Debt Cycle** raising central government debt-to-income ratio and worsening central bank balance sheet
- US in **leveraging-up phase** of long-term debt cycle—haven't entered deleveraging part yet
- Brief deleveragings occurred along the way

### US Private Debt Since 1900

- Current Big Debt Cycle beginning 1945 is obvious in charts
- Peak in private debt (% GDP) in **2008**
- Slight decline since 2008 as US central government and Fed stepped in to help private sector
- Typical of Big Cycle's late stage

### US Government Debt Levels

- Evolving in Big Cycle manner
- **Highest level since 1946** (around end of WWII)
- Projected to be **much higher in future** (CBO 10- and 20-year projections)
- Central government **deleveraging up** while private sector deleverages

### Relationship Between Private and Public Debt

- Most important dynamic: **government tends to acquire more debt when private sector is acquiring less**
- Example: government debt-to-GDP increased dramatically since 2008 while private sector debt-to-GDP declined
- Central government goes deeper into debt to provide private sector with more support

### Debt Service Projections

- Currently at **~100% of government revenue**
- Projected to rise to **~150% in 15 years**
- Unthinkable scenario requires believing government will: 1) roll over debt coming due, 2) sell new debt to fund deficit, 3) existing debt holders won't sell
- Requires belief that lenders will continue lending to government despite risk

### Interest Rates and Inflation

**10-Year Treasury Bond Rate and 3-Year Moving Average Inflation**:

> "The relationship between interest rates and the inflation rate is important because when interest rates are high relative to the inflation rate there is an incentive to save and earn the interest rate, and when interest rates are low relative to the inflation rate there is an incentive to borrow and hold assets that benefit from inflation and the growth that low interest rates foster."

- Bond yield = expected inflation rate + expected real bond yield
- Both affect value of money and debt as storehouse/cost of funds
- On upswing of Big Cycle: all short-term cyclical swings in bond yields were **higher than previous ones until 1981**
- Each short-term cyclical swing 1981-2020 was **lower than previous** until nominal rates nearly hit 0% and real rates significantly negative
- Reflects big cycle in inflation expectations and real interest rate movements

### Real Bond Yields

- After 1997: using real yield on 10-year Treasury inflation-protected bond
- **Real bond yield = most important number to watch in financial world**
- Shows what real return you can get on wealth (free of inflation and default risk)
- Most foundational rate for all capital markets—earn more requires cleverness

> "It is the single best indicator of whether it is better to be a borrower-debtor or a lender-creditor"

- When real rates low: easier to borrow and convert to profits
- When real rates high: opposite
- Great tool for central banks to modulate credit and economic activity
- Real bond yield averaged **~2% over last 100 years**—rate neither too low for lender-creditors nor too high for borrower-debtors
- Periods of great difference from 2% = times of excessively cheap or expensive credit contributing to big swings in Big Debt Cycle

### Breakeven Inflation Rate

- Nominal bond yields vs. inflation-indexed bonds' real yields shows **breakeven inflation rate** (market's bet)
- Can make money betting against that rate if inflation higher/lower than market believes
- Markets pretty tough to beat—use as naïve but good estimate
- Bond yield/price consists of "discounted" inflation rate + discounted real interest rate
- Author always watches them separately, often trades the two pieces separately

### The 10-Year Rate as Governor of Capital Markets

> "I always think about the 10-year interest rate and its two parts because it is the most important governor of all capital markets."

**Author's Personal Journey with Inflation-Indexed Bonds**:
- Invested in non-US inflation-indexed bonds currency-hedged when no US market existed
- **David White** of Rockefeller Foundation asked for 5%/year investment solution—prompted thinking about leveraging/hedging non-US inflation-indexed bonds
- Led **Bridgewater** to become largest global inflation-indexed bond manager
- Invited to work on design of **Treasury Inflation-Protected Security (TIPS)** market with **Larry Summers** at US Treasury
- Real market showing real bond yields became foundational to investment thinking
- Believes inflation-indexed bond markets worldwide are underappreciated and underused as indicators and storehouses of wealth

### The Yield Curve

> "The relationship between short-term rates and long-term rates (i.e., the yield curve) is very important because when short-term interest rates are high relative to long-term rates that indicates money is tight and encourages the holding and lending of cash, which becomes more attractive than borrowing and investing in other assets."

- Movements in asset attractiveness affect **nominal interest rate yield curve** (difference between 10-year yield and nominal short rate)
- Higher interest rate normally required by lender-creditors to hold longer-term debt
- Long-term rates higher than cash rates provide reward/inducement for lending
- When central bank wants to slow credit/economic growth: raises short-term rates relative to long-term
- When wants to stimulate: does opposite
- **High real yields + flat/inverted yield curve** = tight money, good for lender-creditors, bad for borrower-debtors
- **Low real yields + positive yield curve** = good for borrower-debtors, bad for lender-creditors
- Extreme shifts by central banks lead to extremely good/bad environments and high volatility
- Disruptive to economies, causes pain and inefficiencies

### Author's Proposed Monetary Policy Approach

> "I think the Fed should not be as extreme and volatile as it has been in its use of interest rates to influence monetary policy. If I were running monetary policy, my goal would be to keep the long-term real interest rate relatively stable at a rate that balances the needs of both borrower-debtors and lender-creditors and doesn't contribute to the making of debt bubbles and busts. That would mean seeking to have the real Treasury bond yield around 2%, varying that target by something like 1%, and targeting the yield curve slope so that a) the short-term rate is about 1% below the long-term rate and b) the short-term rate divided by the long-term rate is about 70%, give or take about 2% and about 50%, respectively."

- Fewer big/volatile swings in real rates and yield curves → less volatility
- Less harm to borrower-debtors and lender-creditors (and everything they affect in economy)
- Would allow better planning for both parties
- More consistent policy gives borrower-debtors and lender-creditors reasonable expectations
- Provides stable cost of funds and real returns → stable capital markets → stable economic conditions
- Enhances efficiencies in running capital markets and economy

### Credit Spreads

- **Treasury rate** ≠ rate people/companies/local governments borrow at
- Watching **credit spreads** is helpful
- Chart shows average **Baa corporate spread** since 1920

### Debt Service Components

- Interest owed = **amount borrowed × interest rate**
- Plus **principal to be paid back** = **total debt service**
- Debt service roughly flat 1950-2000 because government debt levels roughly flat/falling slightly relative to revenue
- Principal payments roughly flat to slightly falling over that period
- Interest payments rose slightly 1950-1990 as average interest rate on government debt slowly rose
- Fell 1990-~2022 as average interest rate slowly fell

**Future Projections (CBO)**:
- Next 10 and 20 years: very different picture
- Central government debt levels high and projected to rise fast
- Interest rate on high debts projected to rise
- Will cause **big increase in government debt service relative to revenue**
- Produces significant squeeze on spending unless more borrowing (likely financed by central bank)
- **Therein lies the problem**

### Who Holds US Government Debt?

- Borrowed lot from **central bank**
- Borrowed lot from **commercial banks**
- About **third from foreign investors**
- Commercial/foreign buyers have had losses as rates risen
- Have more US debt as % of holdings than makes sense financially
- Some worried US government won't pay them back the way it didn't before WWII—becoming sellers
- Biggest foreign holders acquired because wanted to store buying power in most widely used/accepted currency of greatest/most credible world power (**dollar = leading reserve currency of leading world power**)
- Looking ahead: hard to imagine big buyers/holders will buy huge amounts of US Treasuries in future like they did in past
- Especially if key underpinnings weaken: a) US government irresponsibly handles debt and domestic/foreign policy issues, b) US government threatens to sanction by withholding debt payments, c) returns from holding debt are bad, d) US loses economic/geopolitical prominence

### Two Major Waves of Money Printing

**1980-2008**: Lowering interest rates sufficient to keep debt service affordable as debt levels kept rising

**Post-2008**: When rates nearly hit zero (as in post-1933 period):

> "When rates nearly hit zero in 2008, as they did in the post-1933 period, private market demand for the bonds was inadequate to meet the supply so the central bank stepped in to print money and buy the bonds, which put downward pressure on longer-term rates. It happened in two major waves—one in response to the 1929-33 debt-crisis-induced Great Depression when interest rates hit 0% in the post-1933 period, and again in response to the 2008 debt-crisis-induced Great Recession when interest rates hit 0%."

- Can see in chart: small circles indicate beginning of money printing and rates hitting zero
- This discovery led to first understanding of how Big Debt Cycle works

### Central Bank Balance Sheet Issues

**Federal Reserve and Other Central Banks**:
- Debt assets provide **lower returns than costs required to service liabilities**
- Modest rise in interest rates in recent tightening caused Fed to take **modest operating losses**
- If bonds marked to market: Fed's losses ~**$700 billion or 2.5% of GDP**
- Relatively minor compared to central bank's capacity to obtain funding
- **Red flag**—would become major problem if big selling of US debt
- Typically happens when debt perceived as risky asset

**For Countries That Can Print Own Money**:
- Would lead to either: a) big/intolerable rise in nominal and real interest rates (contracting credit, severe economic contraction), or b) big central bank money printing and debt buying + credit provision (devaluation of debt and money)
- Big central bank losses and bad conditions increase likelihood central bank's independence questioned

**For Countries With Debt in Reserve Currency Not Their Own**:
- Conditions much worse

---

## Chapter 11: 1945 to 1971—A Linked (Hard) Monetary System

### Introduction to Monetary Policy 0 (MP0)

- WWII ended prior world order, caused transition to current world order
- Biggest war winners (US, UK, allies + Soviet Union and allies) determined rules of new world order including **new world monetary system**
- Split from start between US/allies and Soviet Union/allies
- **1944**: US, UK, allies created **Bretton Woods system** (named after location in New Hampshire)
- Gold-linked (hard) monetary system
- Author calls this **Monetary Policy 0** to signify first type in sequence of monetary systems/approaches dealing with Big Debt Cycle's evolving conditions

### Characteristics of MP0 System

> "A Monetary Policy 0 system looks like most prior monetary systems that existed throughout the millennia with 'paper' money being linked to the real money (gold), which was held in banks (in this case, central banks). In an MP0 system, currency can be used to buy a designated hard asset (most often gold) at a set price, and because of that ability, the supply of the currency is supposedly limited."

- If currency supply becomes too large, price should fall
- Too much currency relative to backing item (gold) → people exchange money for that item
- Worsens imbalance between money amount and hard asset amount money backed by
- Fear of doom loop intended to limit money creation and support money value
- **Problem**: Never worked long-term—even with hard asset link, governments create more money/debt than they should
- Leads to more claims on asset (gold) than money convertible into it at specified price
- Consequences: almost always "run on the bank" with people rushing to convert, breaking of promise to deliver hard asset

### The Bretton Woods Gold-Linked System (1945-1971)

> "The gold-linked MP0 system set up at Bretton Woods lasted until 1971, during which time dollars, which were then considered like checks with no intrinsic value, were exchangeable for gold, which was considered the real money, at a fixed exchange rate. Other currencies were exchangeable for dollars at agreed-upon and changeable rates."

- **27-year period** with **five short-term debt/economic cycles**
- Wiggles around uptrend in debt relative to incomes during period
- Author will describe how period unfolded, including all five big forces

### Bretton Woods System Specifics

- US had about **two-thirds of world's gold** held by US Treasury
- **Dollar became world's reserve currency**
- Other countries had own currencies—to get gold from US central bank, had to buy dollars then use dollars to buy gold
- **Only countries' central banks allowed to buy gold**
- Individuals prohibited from buying gold with paper money
- In US and most countries: **illegal for citizens to own gold**
- Governments wanted people to save in debt assets to build credit system
- Didn't want debt assets to compete with gold

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## Chapter 12: 1971 to 2008—A Fiat Money, Interest-Rate-Driven Monetary Policy

### The Post-War Bretton Woods System and US Dominance

- Bretton Woods system created for US and allied countries wanting to join; UK became subordinate power with weakened finances, while US enriched by entering WWII late
- Soviet Union opted out, maintained independent monetary system outside US-dominated order
- **Main geopolitical competition**: US (capitalist democracy) vs Soviet Union (communist autocracy)
- US provided **Marshall Plan** and financial support to rebuild European allies, leveraging reserve currency status and ~50% of world GDP
- US possessed world's reserve currency, giving great buying power that it eventually abused

### China's "Century of Humiliation" and Civil War

- **China's "Century of Humiliation" (1839-1945)**: foreign powers controlled parts of China, conditions deteriorated, government collapsed
- Japan took Taiwan in 1895, returned to China by winning powers after WWII
- **1945-49 civil war**: hard-right **Kuomintang** vs hard-left **Chinese Communist Party**
- Communists drove Kuomintang to Taiwan, aligned with Russia; US alienated China
- Taiwan now critical for chip production—more important than oil was in previous cycle

### Post-War Innovation and UK Decline

- **1950s innovation boom**: American scientists and entrepreneurs (capitalist-financed with government support) created transformative technologies
- 1956: artificial intelligence invented; 1957: first satellite launched; mid-1950s: internet's technical foundations developed
- **UK heavily indebted** with colonies in 40+ countries it couldn't afford to maintain
- UK experienced classic debt devaluation cycle: **30% currency devaluation in 1949**, followed by series of devaluations to relieve debt burdens
- Debt holders suffered inevitable losses as controlled territories were lost
- 1956: Egypt took Suez Canal—UK bond holders sold
- 1967: another financial crisis and major devaluation
- 1976: UK went to IMF for financial help
- Author notes UK's decline described in detail in *Principles for Dealing with the Changing World Order*

### US Money Printing and Gold Drain (1960s)

- **Early 1960s**: US short-term money/credit cycle was expansionary—great for markets until inflation rose
- **1965-66**: inflation hit 3.8%, Fed tightened policy, **inverting yield curve for first time since 1929**
- **1968**: peak inflation-adjusted S&P 500 price for next 25 years due to Big Cycle influences
- Led to **1969-70 recession**
- Long period of poor stock/bond performance primarily due to money creation and devaluation needed to service debts
- Author learned paradigm about making money in all market types and developed different mindset from equity-focused investors

### Cuban Missile Crisis and Geopolitical Lessons

- **1962 Cuban Missile Crisis**: brought US and Soviet Union to brink of nuclear war
- Author (age 13) expected major market impact, but stock market barely reacted
- Both sides pulled missiles (US from Turkey, USSR from Cuba), claimed victory without revealing concessions
- Taught author about **brinkmanship diplomacy** and how markets behave during high-stakes conflicts
- JFK assassination (November 1963) also had only brief market effect
- Vietnam War ("guns") and domestic social programs ("butter") followed
- **Key investment lesson**: what matters to markets is money from investments, not political headlines
- Big political events don't matter until they affect cash flows
- Most global threats sound worse than they are—leaders typically step back from brink
- However, conflicts can impact supply chains and currencies; rare occasions when leaders don't back down become consequential

### China-Soviet Split and US-China Rapprochement

- **1960s geopolitical swing**: China and Soviet Union shifted from "friendly" to "enemy" countries
- Corresponding shift: China and US moved from "enemies" to "friends"
- **Henry Kissinger's secret China visit (1971)** then **Nixon's visit (early 1972)** set stage for China's opening after Mao Zedong died in 1976
- Small seeds of change grew into enormous impacts affecting all five forces

### US Overspending and Breaking the Gold Link

- **1945-71 period**: US overspent and financed by borrowing, especially 1960s Vietnam War and "war on poverty"
- **Paper-money promises to give real money (gold) far exceeded central bank reserves**—bad finances grew slowly until blowup
- Early 1950s-60s: countries accepted paper dollars for goods/services, wanted to accumulate dollars as savings
- As Germany and Japan recovered economically, US balance of payments worsened
- **Late 1960s**: holders of paper money turned it in for real money (gold), so **US central bank's gold reserves steadily declined**

> **Key principle**: "During times when there is too much debt relative to the quantity of money that is needed to service debts, the need to either increase the amount of money that exists and/or cut the amount of debt there is leads governments to break their promises and do some combination of a) raising the amount of money and credit, b) reducing the amount of debt (e.g., by restructuring it), and/or c) preventing the free-market ownership and movement of the hard money (e.g., gold). At such times, there is a run away from bad money to good money that the government wants to stop. This often leads to prohibiting good money from being freely held and freely move."

- **Charles de Gaulle** (French president) openly called for monetary system reform in 1965
- Other dollar holders caught on, run accelerated, US spending/deficits continued
- **US central bank lacked enough gold to meet obligations** to exchange paper money at promised price

### Nixon Closes the Gold Window (August 15, 1971)

- **Sunday night, August 15, 1971**: **Nixon announced on television US would no longer allow dollar holders to turn dollars in for gold**
- **Ended the monetary system and money as we knew it**—immediately devalued money, raised inflation, made debt payment easier
- Author was clerking on NYSE floor at the time—expected stock market crash
- Instead, **Monday was best day for market that year—stocks up >3%**
- Author studied history, found **1933 Roosevelt** did exact same thing (defaulted on gold exchange promise) for exact same reason (more gold promises than gold reserves, running out during bank run)
- Same effect both times: devaluation, big market rallies in stocks and gold
- Only difference: Roosevelt used radio, Nixon used television

### Author's Investment Epiphany

> **Critical lesson**: "when there is a big debt problem that is intolerably painful, central banks will 'print money' and distribute it to make it easier for debtors to pay their debts, which will devalue the money and debt relative to other assets."

- Helped author make money and avoid painful losses throughout career

## Chapter 12 (continued): 1971-82 Stagflation and Political Shift

### The New Fiat Monetary System (MP1)

- **August 1971 breakdown** replaced gold-linked system with **fiat monetary system where central banks stimulated/restrained debt/credit/money growth by changing interest rates**
- Author calls this **Monetary Policy 1 (MP1)**
- **MP1 vs MP0 differences**:
  - In MP1, money/credit driven primarily by cost of money (interest rates), not restrained by hard currency link
  - Amount of money/credit was unrestrained
  - World's central banker (Fed) wanted to accommodate this change
- Led to classic combination of **stagflation** (economic stagnation + inflation)

### From 1971 to 1982: Stagflation and Tightening

- **1971-81**: Fed increased money supply by 100%, M2 increased 180%
- CPI up ~140%, stocks up ~30%, gold up 10x
- Stock prices fell 45% in real terms
- **Debtors benefited** (could pay with cheaper dollars), **creditors suffered** (promised money dwindled)
- 10-year Treasury bond holders lost ~40% inflation-adjusted; Baa corporate bonds slightly negative real returns
- **Fed dealt with debt crisis by creating more money/credit**—great debt relief for debtors, great losses for creditors, encouraged borrowing, discouraged lending
- Author gained invaluable lessons about making money in all market types
- Current investors who only experienced positive equity returns make mistake of only buying equity-like investments

### Key Difference: Fiat Money Post-1971

- **Most important difference**: today's money is and has been **fiat money since 1971**
- **Fed (world's central banker) can more freely create money/credit than in the past**
- Other central banks can do same, **affects all mediums of exchange and storehold of wealth**
- Easiest, subtlest way for governments to **alleviate debt burdens and confiscate wealth**
- Studying past fiat monetary systems provides lessons for current debt cycle progression
- Dollar remained world's leading currency despite being terrible storehold in 1970s

### Geopolitical Conflicts Shaped Environment (1971-82)

- **1971-82 period paid to be borrower-debtor** because devaluation starting August 1971 had immediate inflationary effects
- Geopolitical conflicts played role in shaping environment

### The First Oil Shock (1973)

- **1971 monetary easing** got inflation going
- **1973**: British Empire and colonialism breaking down—**big geopolitical shift in Middle East**
- With more money chasing limited oil supply, **Middle Eastern countries created first "oil shock"** causing more inflation
- Fight about money, as it normally is
- Colonized Middle East countries overthrew colonialists, nationalized colonial assets
- **Saudi Arabia, Iran, Iraq, Libya** nationalized oil properties owned by **"Seven Sisters"** (seven major oil companies)
- **October 1973**: war between Arabs and Israelis—oil prices rose significantly

### Debt Cycles Diverged by Country

- **Commodity producers (especially emerging countries) boomed and experienced debt-financed bubbles while US created more money/credit to finance debts**
- Dollars from Europe, US, elsewhere lent to commodity-producing emerging economies, creating **debt bubbles**
- Early 1970s growth of **Eurodollar market**—dollars held in European countries
- High world inflation due to currency devaluations, commodity prices high
- Seemed good to lend to commodity-producing emerging countries
- Fueled boom creating bubble with lender-creditors being US, European, some Japanese banks
- Investment contributed to price declines when money became tight in 1980s

### Two Short-Term Debt Cycles (1971-74 and mid-1970s)

- **1971-74**: easy money, inflation/economic activity rose, oil-exporting countries embargoed oil, sent prices/inflation higher
- **End 1973-1974**: Fed tightened money/credit, raised rates, inverted yield curve—markets/economy into severe decline
- Led to recession, completed short-term debt cycle, new cycle began
- **Next cycle played out same way**: easy money/credit after recession caused activity/inflation to pick up
- **Second oil price shock** caused by internal political and international geopolitical conflicts
- In Iran, shah's domestic order overthrown, US embassy seized, American hostages held—began ongoing Iran conflict
- Both inflationary and humiliating for United States

### Real Interest Rates and Yield Curve Dynamics

- Chart shows average interest rate (90-day T-bill + 10-year Treasury bond) and CPI inflation 1971-1981
- **1970s**: interest rates rose more slowly than inflation, so **real interest rates were low/negative** (as low as -4% vs 2% average)
- Artificially low real rates great for borrower-debtors, terrible for lender-creditors
- Encouraged borrowing and buying, drove inflation up, interest rates followed
- Inflation became so bad changes had to be made, led to reverse
- Two short-term debt cycles clearly visible in charts (vertical lines represent January 1980)

### Labor's Rising Power

- **Workers and labor unions became stronger, raised wage inflation, squeezed company profits**
- **Labor's share of revenue increased from 68% in 1965 to US historical high of 74% in 1980**
- Both reflected and influenced political cycle accompanying debt cycle

### Political Swing to the Right (1979-80)

- **Combination of high inflation, weak dollar, bad economic/business conditions, and geopolitical crises was intolerable for voters**
- Debt/money/economic, domestic-political, and international-geopolitical pendulums swung to extremes—**big changes made, conditions reversed**
- **1979**: **Paul Volcker** appointed Fed chair to shift from very easy to **tightest money and highest interest rates "since birth of Jesus Christ"** (per German Chancellor Helmut Schmidt)
- In reaction to terrible left-leaning government conditions, **Ronald Reagan, Margaret Thatcher, Helmut Kohl** and other right-leaning leaders gained control
- Classic synchronized debt/economic and political swing typically occurring due to people's discontentment

### Volcker's Monetary Tightening

- Chart shows CPI inflation, 3-month and 10-year interest rates, yield curve (3-month minus 10-year)
- From chart: two short-term credit cycles in 1970s, next one emerging early 1980s
- Money made very tight to fight inflation around 1980

### Conservative Policy Shift

- **Shift from liberal to conservative labor policies**
- **Thatcher (UK), Reagan (US), Kohl (Germany)** led strong fights against labor inflation and unions
- **Cut labor's share of revenue pie**, reduced inflation, raised corporate profits
- **Conservative leaders cut taxes on income/corporate profits, pursued tougher geopolitical policies**
- New Iranian leadership released hostages exactly as Reagan took office (responding to threat of severe consequences)
- Thatcher went to war with Argentina over Falkland Islands
- Reagan accelerated Cold War with Soviet Union, eventually ending it

### Markets' Response to Strong Leadership

- **Strong moves by American central government and central bank changed flow of money/power and direction of everything**
- **Markets respected strength, loved combination**: falling interest rates, falling inflation, high real rates, improving profit margins, falling tax rates
- Capitalist's delight—changes in policies and tax changes improved mood, especially willingness to have fights and do difficult things even when painful

### The 1980s Reversal

- **1980s more opposite from than similar to 1970s**—decade of **disinflationary growth, strong stock/bond prices in developed countries, debt bubbles popping, leading to classic inflationary depressions in emerging countries**
- Author deeply involved with markets and circumstances, gained perspective for identifying investment opportunities
- **1982**: author "dead wrong" expecting big debt crisis to cause problems for American banks, stock market, economies
- Failed to anticipate how forceful change in global financial flows away from emerging markets into American markets would be and how well Fed/regulators would protect banks
- Painful lessons about: watching capital flows, diversifying to reduce risk without reducing returns, humility
- Painful experience educated author, radically improved Bridgewater's performance over next 30+ years

### All Big Movements Driven by Debt/Money/Capital Flows

- **All big movements in markets/economics with big effects on politics, geopolitics, and technology development were driven by debt/money/capital flows**
- **Author decided to become expert on capital flows**
- **1971-72 to 1981-82**: very painful, very classic decade of debt restructurings and debt monetizations following archetypal template
- Typical: decade that followed was more opposite than similar

## From 1982 to 1990: Falling Inflation, Strong Growth, and Leveraging Up

### Monetary Policy Shift Benefits Lender-Creditors

- **1979-82 monetary policy changes shifted environment from benefiting borrower-debtors (early 1970s) to benefiting lender-creditors (1980s)**
- **Lowered inflation rate, lowered nominal interest rates while keeping real interest rates relatively high**
- Charts show interest rates and inflation through 1990—demonstrates how different 1980s were from 1970s
- Monetary moves ending 1970s' rising inflation/nominal rates/low real rates created 1980s' falling inflation and relatively high real rate environment
- Began long period of falling interest rates
- With profit margins widening, 1980s almost ideal for markets/economy
- Strong growth with falling inflation, falling interest rates, big stock/bond gains in US and most developed countries
- Early 1980s to early 1990s: inflation fell significantly, interest rates and credit tightness fell even more

### Emerging Market Debt Crisis

- **Transfer of wealth came from borrower-debtors holding high-interest debt liabilities/assets, especially emerging market borrower-debtors who borrowed in dollars with earnings in local currency, and those who lent to them (especially US multinational banks)**
- Classic cycle experienced: high rates made dollar debt expensive, drove dollar rally
- Countries with debt liabilities/assets in tight foreign currency (US dollars) faced debt default problems
- Countries with debts in currencies they could print had currencies plunge due to money printing (monetary inflation) and monetary deflations in currencies they owed and couldn't print

### Classic Debt Busts in Emerging Markets

- **Late 1970s debt bubbles turned into classic debt busts with big tightening that tortured both sides with ugly deleveraging in 1980s**
- **Countries facing debt busts (many emerging countries) experienced classic full debt cycle over 20+ years**:
  - **Inflationary depressions** due to great debt monetizations depreciating local currency money/debt
  - **Deflationary debt default problems** in foreign currency debt they couldn't monetize
- Cycle transpired per template in Part II
- Debt busts created classic "lost decade" with inflationary depressions and classic debt workouts for lending banks
- **Eventually, 1991**: classic end to debt bust as described in Part II—local currency debt devalued, foreign currency debt restructured
- Near cycle end, overly indebted governments sold government assets to build forex reserves, linked domestic currencies to dollar, completing Big Debt Cycles

### Country-Specific Cases and Geopolitical Shifts

- **Each country experienced own cycle**—will explore China and Japan in Chapters 15 and 16
- **Important geopolitical shifts during this time impacted Big Cycle for all nations**

### Soviet Decline and China's Rise

- **1980s geopolitical landscape changed**: Soviet Union declined, China rose, wealth gaps increased
- **Changes mostly driven by Soviet Union's inadequate financial and economic system**
- US had much more money and productivity, outcompeted Soviet Union in everything, notably military
- Led to Soviet Union's debt, economic, currency, political, and geopolitical collapses
- Manifest in fall of Berlin Wall (late 1989) and official Soviet Union collapse (December 1991)

### Deng Xiaoping's Transformation of China (1978)

- **Deng Xiaoping coming to power in 1978 brought big changes in 1980s with big impacts on changing world order until now**
- **Deng's ascension ushered beginning of China's capitalist-like era and start of its big debt/credit/money/economic cycle**
- Before then, little debt/credit/savings/economic activity
- **Deng changed that by creating China's "open door" and "reform" policies**, bringing in foreign capitalists with money and talent
- **Swing from pure/extreme communism to market-oriented, capitalism-infused "communism" had huge impact on China and rest of world**
- **Unleashed wave of productivity making China greatest trading and manufacturing power ever**—able to produce tradable goods at much lower costs than elsewhere
- Huge impact on China and other countries, explored later
- Author's China relationships and financial markets knowledge allowed contribution to and close observation of China's transformation
- China's Big Cycle evolution explained in detail in Chapter 15
- China became extremely productive, swamped world with attractively priced items, earned/lent tons of money to Americans and others
- Americans got goods, Chinese got Americans' debt—author still working out who got better deal

### 1980s Technology Developments

- **Most important big inventions**: laptop computers, lithium-ion batteries, internet, digitization of thinking, apps, DNA profiling
- Big advancements in GPS, video game consoles, microprocessors, satellite television
- Americans remained leading inventors and investors while other countries were leading producers
- **1980s technology development force** (entrepreneurs supported by capitalists) led to internet being developed, launching World Wide Web (1991) and dot-com bubble emerging (1990s)
- Led to **dot-com bubble bursting (2000)** when Fed tightened money to rein in rapid debt-financed speculation

## From 1990 to 2000: More Disinflation and Leveraging Up, Which Led to a Bubble

### Navigating the 1990s

- **1990s brought many developments that seemed giant at the time, barely memorable in retrospect**
- Author wonders if providing too much or not enough detail
- At the time events unfolded, every minute seemed like eternity; now struggles to remember them

> **Author's principle**: "everything seems bigger up close. This has helped me keep things in perspective and navigate changes."

- Happy to have navigated well due to what learned and trying to convey in this study
- Hopes to show events in Big Cycle context so readers can put things in perspective, see how five big forces work and are interrelated

### Mid-1980s to Early 1990s Dynamics

- **Mid-1980s and early 1990s**: tight money and abundant commodity supplies led commodity producers to sell at low prices

<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## From 2000 to 2008: The Bubble Burst and 2008 Crisis

### The 2000 Bubble Burst and Post-9/11 Contraction

- **1995-99 tech bubble**: Early excitement over new technologies (Wi-Fi, smartphones, e-commerce, GPS, video games, AI) financed by debt/equity cycles, similar to railroads/steam engines in previous Big Cycles
- Bubble burst in **March 2000** when Fed tightened monetary policy after rising inflation
- **Nasdaq fell ~80%** from peak
- **September 11, 2001**: World Trade Center and Pentagon attacks initiated "war on terror" and wars in Afghanistan/Iraq
- Both events contributed to short-term debt cycle contraction

### Two Short-Term Cycles (2000-2008)

- Charts show dynamic well: unemployment fell to low levels, stock prices rose to bubble levels in phase (1), then reversed in early 2000s (2)
- Recession reduced inflation → next short-term debt cycle easing → recovery (3)
- **2006-2007**: Another classic bubble developed, most prominent in real estate mortgages but also in banks and companies

### The End of MP1 (1981-2008)

> "In the 27 years from 1981 (when interest rates hit 'the highest levels since the birth of Jesus Christ') to 2008 (when interest rates hit 0%), the Big Cycle consisted of four short-term debt/credit/economic cycles. From 1981 until 2008, every cyclical high and every cyclical low in interest rates was lower than the one before it, until interest rates hit 0%."

- **MP1 ended**: Interest rate-driven monetary policy replaced by quantitative-easing-driven monetary policy (**MP2**)

### Bridgewater's 2008 Crisis Response

- Author studied big cycles from 1918-1945, from WWI end to new monetary system post-WWII
- Put rules into investment system: if debt contraction crisis + short-term Treasury/fed funds rates near 0%, bet on bad contraction until central government/banks become very stimulative (like March 1933)
- This understanding enabled successful crisis navigation for clients

> "This downward trend in interest rates and increase in debt burdens set the stage for the next major shift in monetary policy, which we will explore in the next chapter."

### Other Forces in the 2000s

**Technology Growth Despite 2000 Bust**

- Internet tech industry and effects continued growing and improving rapidly
- **Social media began mid-2000s**: Facebook (2004), YouTube (2005)
- **iPhone released 2007**: Created "everything device" with phone, camera, many app tools
- Internet/computing impacted nearly every aspect of life
- US led developments, though China began copying and competing effectively

**China's Rise as Manufacturing Power**

- China and emerging markets became more competitive in producing most everything
- From everyday goods (1990s/2000s) to electric vehicles and high-tech goods now
- Wonderful for Chinese sellers (earned money) and American buyers (good-value purchases)
- Put many US/European manufacturing workers out of work
- **US-China trade dynamic**: Chinese sellers lent money back to US to fund deficits, mirroring earlier Japanese pattern

> "This dynamic was good for the capitalists who owned the means of production and not good for the workers who were displaced."

- China put sizable foreign exchange reserves into US Treasuries (dollar as world's leading reserve currency)
- Enabled US government to ramp up deficits/debts without major consequence (so far)
- Helped keep global goods inflation down, allowed easier monetary policy, contributed to bull markets in stocks

**Geopolitical Seeds of Conflict**

- Wars in Iraq/Afghanistan occurred, but not big wars between major powers
- **Seeds being sown for conflict**:
  - European Union and NATO continued taking in Eastern European countries, moving closer to Russian border
  - As China got richer, began rivaling US as geopolitical power, increasing tensions

**Climate Change and Nature Risks**

- Climate change first received significant global policy attention in 1990s
- Began bringing destructive weather events: **Hurricane Katrina** (New Orleans, 2005)
- Impacts grew more costly over time
- Novel virus outbreaks monitored: **SARS** (2002-03), **H1N1** (2009)
- Neither as disruptive as feared but symptomatic of challenges to come

**Political Environment**

- President: moderate rightist **George W. Bush**
- House and Senate narrowly controlled by Republicans
- Government much more bipartisan than at time of writing
- Republicans voted across party lines more often

**European Integration**

- Need for European countries to operate as economic unit and compete with other blocs led to **Exchange Rate Mechanism (ERM)**
- Major European countries linked currencies in ERM
- System of separate currencies with separate monetary policies doesn't work → ERM broke up
- "One of the great trades of the 1990s for those who understood how currencies work"
- Eventually led to abandoning individual currencies/central banks → **euro** and **European Central Bank** (1999)
- Major countries unified despite challenge of bringing together different, independent peoples with long history of fighting
- In globalized world, not viable as individual nations economically or geopolitically
- EU remains highly fragmented union, declining in competitiveness

**US Budget Success**

- President Clinton succeeded in transforming large budget deficit into budget surplus
- "One of a number of cases worth remembering to help us think about how to handle things well"

## Chapter 13: 2008 to 2020—Fiat Money and Debt Monetization

### The 2008 Global Financial Crisis

- **Big deleveraging**: Led by mortgage/real estate sector financed by lots of debt
- Debt problems spread quickly to affect almost everyone in all countries (like Great Depression in 1930s)
- Debt crisis started with mortgage/real estate, spread to overleveraged banks, companies, individuals
- Knocked down financial assets and real economy
- **Unemployment hit 10%** in late 2009
- Major stock indices down over 50% from 2007 peak

### Birth of MP2: Debt Monetization

> "In late 2008, the interest-rate-driven monetary system (Monetary Policy 1) could no longer be used to create money and credit anymore because interest rates hit 0%, and because that could not continue, central banks had to make up for inadequate free-market demand to buy these debt assets by printing money and buying the assets themselves."

- **MP2 = Monetary Policy 2**: Central banks buy large quantities of debt and provide credit funded with balance sheets
- Essentially printing money, **debt monetization**, and **quantitative easing**
- Central bank creates/provides money and credit to government and marketplace to make up for inadequate private market lending
- Began 2008, first time this monetary policy used since **1933** (75 years earlier)
- Such moves to monetize debt occurred throughout history, symptomatic of late phase of long-term debt cycle

### Central Bank as Big Creditor

- In this Big Debt Cycle phase, **central bank becomes big buyer and owner of debt** (the big creditor) rather than private investors
- Central bank doesn't mind losses from holding devalued debt, doesn't worry about getting squeezed
- Can continue preventing debt crisis by printing money and buying debt
- Willing/able to lose lots of money and have negative net worth to protect spending ability of government and private sector even when finances are bad
- Visible via central bank balance sheet changes: holdings of debt assets acquired by providing cash/credit to debt sellers
- **US, Europe, Japan central banks** own roughly 15%, 30%, 40% of central government debt respectively
- Own roughly 5%, 10%, 20% of total debt respectively

### US Recovery Charts (2008-2010)

- Charts show timing of hitting 0% interest rate bottom and printing-of-money expansion of Fed's balance sheet
- Fed responded quickly to problem—much more than during Great Depression
- Markets and economy rebounded quickly

**Key observations**:
- Real bond yield averaged ~2% over last 100 years (dashed line)
- Neither too low for borrower-debtors nor too high for lender-creditors
- Periods of great differences from 2% were times of excessively cheap or expensive credit/debt that contributed greatly to big swings in Big Debt Cycle

### MP2 Era: Two Short-Term Cycles with Growing Monetization

- **2008-2020 MP2 era**: Two short-term debt/credit/economic cycles occurred
- In each, amount of debt creation AND debt monetization greater than the one before it

### Global Transition to MP2

- While 2008 crisis began in US, spilled over into global crisis
- Virtually all developed world central banks followed US and transitioned from MP1 to MP2
- Many emerging market central banks did too
- Actions pushed up prices of financial assets, pushed down yields for lender-creditors, created cheap money for borrower-debtors
- **Stimulative monetary policies further benefited the rich** who had financial assets
- Government bailout of banks contributed to perception system favored rich, heightened animosity toward rich capitalists
- Especially those who seemed to cause problems, got away free, and made lots of money
- US managed private sector debt problems and engineered economic recovery even as public debt kept rising (kicking can down road; more Chapter 18)

### Hollowing Out of Middle Class and Political Polarization

- Continuing increases in Chinese/foreign imports took away American jobs
- New technology also taking away jobs
- **Forces contributed to hollowing out of middle class**, increased tensions between "elites/capitalists" and "proletariat"

> "China came to hold a lot of US debt assets and the US lost lots of jobs in uncompetitive businesses, which in the US contributed to the creation of large wealth and values differences, anti-China sentiment, and great political and social polarization."

- People hurting economically believed "elites" running things and system were maximizing profits at expense of American workers
- Combined with 2008 debt/economic crisis and government bailout of financial institutions benefiting asset holders more than common man
- Had big impact on domestic conflict

### Rise of Populism

> "As a result, the financial crisis led to a shift toward populism of the right (e.g., the Tea Party movement) and populism of the left (e.g., Occupy Wall Street)."

- **Conflict between politically/socially right and left became greater** in response to growing wealth/values differences in most countries, especially United States
- Rise of populism of right, especially among non-college-educated, non-urban white population
- Led to **Donald Trump's election in 2016**

### Trump's Transformative Shift

- Changed American approach to domestic order and world order in profound ways
- Not fully understood for many years (at time of writing March 2025, still not fully understood)
- More extensively described at end of Chapter 14

> "President Trump produced a shift in the domestic, international, economic, political, and geopolitical orders to be much more aggressive, top-down/autocratic, rightist, nationalistic, protectionist, and militaristic."

- **Shifts characterized by increased confrontation and reduced cooperation**
- Reflected in breakdown of multilateral organizations and increased unilateralism
- Analogous to shifts that occurred many times throughout history, most recently before WWI and WWII

### Trump Administration Policies

- Rightist policies: big tax cuts for companies/individuals
- Appointment of three conservative justices to Supreme Court
- Big cuts in government regulations
- Renegotiation of trade and military support deals with other countries
- Big tariffs and immigration restrictions
- Cutting income/corporate taxes and reducing regulations helped stock prices rise and economy grow
- Unemployment rate fell to 50-year low of **3.5% by end of 2019**
- Then **COVID**, first major global pandemic since 1918-20 H1N1, came along in early 2020

### Big Cycles Transpiring in Classic Ways

> "The big debt, political, and geopolitical cycles and the relationships between them have been unfolding in pretty classic ways so they have been contributors to the Overall Big Cycle transpiring in pretty classic ways. What we saw and are now seeing are these three big cycles transpiring along with big disruptions coming from nature (i.e., the pandemic and climate change) and with big advances in technology, especially artificial intelligence (which should greatly improve productivity and be disruptive in other ways, too)."

### Europe's Debt Crisis: Greece Example

- Europe in 2012: 17 countries in Eurozone, some debtors, some creditors → made process more difficult
- Overly indebted countries with debts denominated in currency they couldn't print (euro) suffered as described
- European Central Bank handled situation in typical way
- **Greece as example** of cycle for heavily indebted countries that couldn't print own currency

**Classic Debt Crisis Template Applied to Greece**:

**1. Private sector and central government get deep in debt**
- 10 years prior to 2008: Greece's total debt as % of GDP increased ~90%, from 160% to 250%
- Impetus: Greece joining euro made debt assets seem safer (no devaluation risk, ECB backstop)
- Capital flowed in from across Eurozone, debt increased in every sector

**2. Private sector suffers debt crisis, central government gets deeper in debt to help**
- When 2008 financial crisis hit, Greek government responded with stimulus and bigger deficits
- Added to debt; because couldn't monetize debt, worsened rather than alleviated debt crisis
- Greece entered deep depression

**3. Central government experiences debt squeeze—free-market demand for debt falls short of supply, creating government debt problem**
- Debt crisis became acute public sector debt crisis in late 2009
- Greek government revealed substantial underreporting of own debt and deficits

**4. Selling of government debt leads to: a) free-market-driven tightening of money/credit, b) weakening of economy, c) downward pressure on currency, d) declining reserves as central bank attempts to defend currency**
- Crushing debt burdens and reporting fraud made Greek debt less desirable to foreign investors
- Became sellers of Greek debt; Greece needed more stimulus to offset depression-like conditions
- Unavoidably pursued austerity, causing depression to get deeper and government finances worse as tax receipts dried up
- Result: massive sell-off in Greek debt, raising interest rates even higher and worsening debt problem
- By 2012, short-term interest rates in Greece spiked to over 70%
- Greek debt increased another ~70% of GDP, combination of austerity not working and GDP declining (dynamic called "ugly deleveraging")

**5. When debt crisis and interest rates can't be lowered (hit 0%), central bank "prints" (creates) money and buys bonds to ease credit and make easier to service debt**
- Actually doesn't literally print; essentially borrows reserves from commercial banks paying very short-term interest rate
- ECB stepped in with huge crisis money printing and buying of debt, expanded balance sheet like Fed
- Wasn't nearly enough; became politically toxic as more financially stable European countries decried bailout of Greece
- Worried one way or another they would have to pay for it

**6. If interest rates rise, central bank loses money because interest rate paid on liabilities > interest rate received on debt assets bought**
- Did not see this dynamic in this case
- Typically happens when central bank purchased significant government debt at fixed rate, financed via creating bank reserves paying floating short rates
- Then forced to raise short rates because of currency flight or inflation problem
- Creates negative net interest margin for central bank, forcing continued money printing to cover losses
- European debt crisis case: central bank purchased significant government debt, financed via creating bank reserves
- But Europe as whole did not see inflation problem or currency flight
- ECB not forced to raise interest rates, never had negative net interest margin problem

**7. Debts restructured and devalued, reducing debt burdens**
- Became clear Greece needed debt restructuring
- Money ECB spending on Greece likely to lead to losses
- Even chance Greece would leave euro
- Exceedingly tight credit in Greece crushing economy
- Ultimately, **"the Troika"** (ECB, IMF, European Commission) engineered debt restructuring paired with bailout
- In 2012, restructuring reduced debt burdens by about 50% of GDP

**8. Extraordinary taxes raised, capital flees country and/or capital controls imposed**
- Bank run as smart citizens pulled money out of Greek banks
- Needing money, new taxes introduced
- Capital controls eventually imposed in 2015

**9. Transition from severely devalued currency to stable currency**
- Restructuring enough to end most acute phase of crisis
- Greece stayed in euro
- Reducing debt through explicit restructuring = more painful, drawn-out path
- Greece took years to recover, but did recover as all countries eventually do
- If Greece and other overly indebted countries could have printed currencies they owed, would have gone down classic path previously described

### Other Key Developments (Brief Notes)

**International relations**: Big resets economically and geopolitically led to more allied/enemy geopolitical relationships analogous to 1933-38 period (numerous prior analogous periods). Covered in *Principles for Dealing with the Changing World Order*.

**Climate change**: Got lot of attention. In 2015, **Paris Agreement** initiated attempt to keep global temperatures from rising by more than 2 degrees Celsius. Big costly force that will reshape human and natural worlds.

**New technologies**: Computer chips rapidly advanced, cryptocurrencies launched, self-driving-car features started rolling out, movie streaming became widespread, 4G (then 5G) wireless began, reusable rocket ships began to be used, many more advances made.

## Chapter 14: Since 2020—Pandemic and Big Fiscal Deficits Monetized

### COVID-19 and Monetary Policy 3 (MP3)

- **2020**: World hit with COVID pandemic
- While government financial management principle says monetary policy should be independent of fiscal policy and targeted to pursue inflation and (in US) economic growth goals
- **Without that independence and mandate, there would be politicization and degradation of money supply/value**
- Truth: nearly every sacrosanct rule inevitably tested by reality and starts breaking down later in Big Cycle

> "I call that economic-impact-necessitated change in monetary policy Monetary Policy 3 (MP3). MP3 is when there are coordinated moves between the central government and the central bank, where the government runs large deficits and the bank monetizes them."

- Dynamic inevitably arises when interest rate changes (MP1) and quantitative easing (MP2) no longer effective at helping conditions for most people
- When free-market capitalist system doesn't get job done
- Naturally, capitalist system provides capital to those financially well-off, hold financial assets, able to borrow
- Doesn't provide capital to those who have least and suffer most
- What happened starting in 2008
- Because of COVID pandemic, need not just to make money/credit but get it into hands of specific people and organizations

> "Throughout history, MP3 has been used in similar cases when there were very bad economic conditions and big wealth gaps so interest rate changes or quantitative easing alone could not do what was needed. MP3 typically occurred late in the long-term debt cycle. In this case, it came in two big rounds."

### Debt Levels and Debt Service

- Central government spends a lot and hands out lots of money, getting itself into much more debt while relieving private sector's debt burdens
- Gray vertical lines in charts represent transitions from one type of monetary policy to another
- Charts show US debt levels and central government debt service

### Monetary Policy and Central Bank Health

- Fed's printing of money and buying of government's debt increased a lot from 2008 until late 2021
- Then Fed began tightening to fight inflation
- Pretty classic tightening in response to accelerated inflation
- Tightening and higher interest rates led Fed to lose money on all bonds acquired (shown in chart on right)

### Interest Rates

- Rise in interest rates significant but less than rise in inflation (chart on left)
- Brought real bond yield up to long-term average of ~2% (charts on right and bottom)
- Yield curve inverted
- Discounted 10-year inflation rate stayed steady at around 2% as real yield rose to about 2%
- Moves reflected tightening

### US Political and Social Dynamics Post-2008

**Growing Wealth/Values Polarization**:
- Continuing Chinese/foreign imports took away American jobs at same time new technology taking away jobs
- Contributed to **hollowing out of middle class**
- Increased tensions between "elites/capitalists" and "proletariat"
- China held lot of US debt assets, US lost jobs in uncompetitive businesses
- Created large wealth/values differences, anti-China sentiment, great political/social polarization
- People hurting economically believed "elites" maximizing profits at expense of American workers
- Combined with 2008 debt/economic crisis and government bailout of financial institutions
- Government bailing out banks contributed to perception system favored rich
- Heightened animosity toward rich capitalists, especially those who seemed to cause problems and got away free

**Rise of Populism**:
- Financial crisis led to shift toward **populism of right** (Tea Party movement)
- And **populism of left** (Occupy Wall Street)
- Conflict between politically/socially right and left became greater in response to growing wealth/values differences
- Especially in United States
- Rise of populism of right, especially among non-college-educated, non-urban white population
- Led to Donald Trump's election in 2016
- Changed American approach to domestic order and world order in profound ways
- Wouldn't be understood for many years (at time of writing March 2025, still not fully understood)
- Will be described more extensively at end of Chapter 14

**Trump's Policy Shifts** (succinct summary):

> "President Trump produced a shift in the domestic, international, economic, political, and geopolitical orders to be much more aggressive, top-down/autocratic, rightist, nationalistic, protectionist, and militaristic. These shifts in policies to ones that are characterized by increased confrontation and reduced levels of cooperation (and that are also reflected in the breakdown of multilateral organizations and increased unilateralism) are analogous to those that occurred many times throughout history, most recently in the periods before World War I and World War II."

### Trump Administration Outcomes

- Rightist policies of big tax cuts for companies/individuals
- Appointment of three conservative justices to Supreme Court
- Big cuts in government regulations
- Renegotiation of trade and military support deals
- Big tariffs and immigration restrictions
- Cutting income/corporate taxes and reducing regulations helped stock prices rise and economy grow
- Unemployment rate fell to 50-year low of 3.5% by end of 2019
- Then **COVID**, first major global pandemic since 1918-20 H1N1, came along in early 2020

**For those interested**: These developments and outcomes explained in more detail in *Principles for Dealing with the Changing World Order*
- Analogous to those in early 1930s
- Not unexpected if one understands Big Cycle

> "The big debt, political, and geopolitical cycles and the relationships between them have been unfolding in pretty classic ways so they have been contributors to the Overall Big Cycle transpiring in pretty classic ways."

- What we saw and are now seeing: these three big cycles transpiring along with:
  - Big disruptions coming from nature (pandemic and climate change)
  - Big advances in technology, especially **artificial intelligence** (should greatly improve productivity and be disruptive in other ways too)

### Europe's Cycle Following Template

- Events closely followed template laid out previously
- Though **Europe in 2012 = 17 countries in Eurozone**, some debtors, some creditors → made process more difficult
- Overly indebted countries with debts denominated in currency they couldn't print (euro) suffered in way described
- European Central Bank handled situation in typical way
- Will use **Greece as example** of how cycle transpired for heavily indebted countries that couldn't print own currency (tied to euro)

> "To show how the cycle tracked the template, I will restate what typically happens and then show what actually happened."
<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

## The Wealth and Income Shifts (continued)

### Growing Inequality and Political Polarization

- Labor's share of earnings fell to lowest level since 1950s
- Wealth and income shares of non-college-educated Americans continued declining
- US population became much more divided and politically extreme
- 2020 leadership change: Trump-led rightist Republicans to Biden-led leftist Democrats

### The 2020-2025 Short-Term Debt Cycle

**Pandemic Response and Its Consequences**

- Author shifts from Big Cycle macro perspective to short-term cycle analysis (2020-March 2025)
- Short-term cycles appear micro but significantly affect long-term cycles
- **COVID triggered**: economic contraction → massive fiscal/monetary stimulus (MP3) → inflation surge → wealth redistribution → tightening → modest easing
- Political polarization intensified alongside climate and technology changes

**The 2020-21 Debt Monetization**

- Short-term debt cycle easing began with: a) COVID economic crisis, b) large wealth gaps, c) Democratic political victories (president, House, Senate)
- Response: huge government spending → massive fiscal deficits → debt sales exceeding free-market demand → **central banks (especially Fed) monetized the debt**
- Banks and Japanese institutional investors also bought US Treasury debt
- **Fourth and largest big debt monetization** since original QE in 2008 (first since 1933)
- From 2008 easing cycle peak: nominal Treasury yield fell from 3.7% to 0.5%, real yield from 1.4% to -1%
- **Money and credit became essentially free and plentiful** → great for borrower-debtors, terrible for lender-creditors → orgy of borrowing and bubble formation
- Bubble indicator rose from 18% (2010) to 75% (end of 2020)
- Analogous to: Nifty Fifty (1970-72), Japan bubble (1989-90), dot-com bubble (1999-2000)
- Declining interest rates couldn't fall further, benefiting stocks significantly
- Author estimates interest rate decline raised stock prices ~75% more than pre-crisis peak
- Technology advances and globalization doubled profit margins on average
- Corporate and personal tax declines also boosted asset prices
- **US household wealth in financial assets ("paper wealth") tripled: $32 trillion to $99 trillion** (post-2009 lows through Q2 2024)

**Inflation and Tightening**

- Debt/credit/money surge in 2020 produced big inflation increase
- Inflation exacerbated by supply chain problems and external conflicts (third of five major forces)
- Fed and other central banks shifted short-term debt cycle from easing to tightening
- Maturing debt rolled off rather than being purchased
- Nominal and real interest rates shifted from overwhelmingly favorable to borrowers to more normal levels (e.g., 2% real bond yield)
- Treasury bond nominal yields rose from 0.5% to over 4%; real yields from -1.1% to ~2.5%
- Especially hurt assets with weak/negative profits or requiring new equity funding
- Bubble indicator fell from 75% to 35%; bubble stocks in index fell average of 75%
- **Nominal wealth in stocks/bonds fell ~12% in US; real wealth fell nearly 18%** (largest declines since 2009)
- Cash moved from "trash" to "attractive" status
- Yield curve inverted with classic effects on present values of future cash flows
- Dollar strengthened relative to currencies of countries whose central banks were slower to tighten
- Interest-rate-sensitive sectors hurt: commercial/residential real estate, low/negative cash flow bubble companies (public and private)
- Public stocks suffered more than private markets: "FAANG" stocks and tech-heavy Nasdaq fell ~45% and 33% from peaks
- Private equity, venture capital, real estate not marked down commensurately
- Reluctance to accept markdowns created stand-off; transaction volumes plunged
- Did not weaken economy as much as typical because central government incurred debt rather than private sector
- Central bank absorbed losses, not private sector
- Inflation occurred in wages and compensation as well as goods and services

**Post-Tightening Environment**

- Inflation fell but prices stayed high
- Fed and central banks eased monetary policy, supporting asset prices
- **Artificial intelligence and AI companies became new hot things**, expected to revolutionize economy and life like industrial and digital revolutions
- Great differences emerged in which stocks, companies, and countries performed well
- World capital markets changed with new investment products
- Private credit market developed as modern version of late 1970s/early 1980s junk bond market (more customized, less standardized, more illiquid, inclusive of early-stage companies)
- Large money inflows kept credit spreads down and funded speculative activities

### Internal Political Conflicts Intensify

- **Wealth and values conflicts between right-wing populists and left-wing populists intensified**, most importantly in US
- Political divide between right and left became more extreme
- Big price rises from fiscal/monetary stimulation led to inflation in goods, services, financial assets
- **2024 election outcome**: Inflation and Biden's impaired acuity helped a) rightist/capitalist/social conservative Trump and Republicans decisively defeat b) leftist/socialist/social liberal Kamala Harris and Democrats
- Trump received **mandate for big renovation of central government and country** and prepare for potential war with China and allies
- Close Trump loss would have triggered major domestic conflict

**Other Major Forces**

- Climate changes continued unabated
- **Technological advances, most notably in AI**, led to big shifts in wealth and power

## The Five Big Forces: Debt, Civil War, International War, Acts of Nature, and Technology

### Framework Overview

- Five forces visible daily in news
- Connecting past to present reveals evolution along Big Cycle template lines
- Explained in author's book and five-minute videos about changing world order on **economicprinciples.org**
- **Government debt** obviously big and growing
- **Civil war** between rightists/capitalists/MAGAs and leftists/socialists/communists/woke continues intensifying (though last US election showed rightists clearly beat leftists)
- Shift brought domestic order/disorder cycle to same stage as 1930s
- **International great power conflict** between US/allies and China/allies intensifying
- **Acts of nature force** (climate change) intensifying
- **Technology (especially AI)** will have unimaginable impact, both good and bad
- Five forces are interrelated and move Big Cycle forward
- Internal US fight and external US-China fight increasingly affected by technology war and economic war (need to raise military spending)
- Current situation looks quite like 1930s period

### Transition to China Analysis

- China's Big Cycle review begins with 1945 (new world order) and 1949 (new domestic order)
- Then Japan's Big Cycle, focusing on Big Debt Cycle for valuable lessons

## Chapter 15: China's Big Cycle from 1945-49 Until Now in a Tiny Nutshell

### Introduction

- Author's close relationships with China over 40+ years, including with leaders
- China's Big Cycle as vivid as US's Big Cycle
- Takes ~15 minutes to read

### Before 1945

**Historical Context**

- Chart shows China's Big Cycles back to year 600
- Estimates relative strength using many measures (from *Principles for Dealing with the Changing World Order*)
- Shows biggest Big Cycle waves in Chinese history
- Cycles consistent with Big Cycle template

**China's Big Debt Cycles Since 1865**

- Chart shows 26 years after **Century of Humiliation** began (1839, First Opium War) until now
- 110-year period of humiliation: foreign powers humiliated and exploited China, starting 1839, ending 1949 with Mao and Communist Party establishing People's Republic
- **Big debts built up, wiped out, built up again** (typical pattern)
- Debt wipeout corresponded with internal and external wars (1945-49)
- New order followed, debts rebuilt
- Most years: Chinese money and debt not considered good storeholder of wealth → difficult to build credit and capital markets
- 1989: stock market development began; bond market beginnings → capital markets building began

**Century of Humiliation's Impact on Chinese Leadership**

- Profoundly affected Chinese leaders' perspectives on foreign powers
- Deeply embedded in Chinese leaders' psyche
- Belief that foreign powers' current actions broadly analogous to Century of Humiliation behavior
- **China must have economic and military power** to protect its people and avoid abuse by other powers
- Chinese leaders see US as **hegemon trying to control world order for self-interests** and contain China in areas where US is not part of
- Author not claiming Chinese perspective more true than American—simply describing what happened and touching on both perspectives

### Chinese vs. American Perspectives on Taiwan

- China's leaders view America's Taiwan handling as more intrusive than Americans saw Russia's Cuba influence (1960s)
- Taiwan "indisputably and consistently" recognized as part of China by all world powers since WWII end, 90 miles from mainland
- Chinese civil war led to Kuomintang and Chiang Kai-shek taking control (1971)
- UN General Assembly recognized mainland People's Republic as "the only legitimate representative of China to the United Nations"
- Reinforced "One China" policy: only one China, Taiwan is part of China
- Chinese leaders expect to eventually take control of Taiwan and parts of South China Sea
- Most Americans see China as big and growing threat to US and existing US-led world order
- Chinese viewed as ideologically threatening communists who autocratically control their people
- Great ideological war with capitalist/democratic/Abrahamic vs. [Chinese system]
- Some in Washington and Beijing see this as last and biggest great cultural/religious/economic and possibly military war
- Author won't elaborate further (too large a digression)
- Points out Chinese leaders' perspective and its big effect on thinking and actions
- Very long Chinese civilization history makes leaders very aware of Big Cycle

### China's Greatest Strengthening Period

- **China had strengthening over last 50 years greater in magnitude than any other country's in history**
- Led to becoming great power approaching US power
- **US and China entered classic period of great power conflict**
- Charts show aggregate power readings since 1825 and US-China conflict gauge since 1963
- China's relative power fell during Century of Humiliation, then rose significantly
- Now close to rivaling US
- Leading to classic great power conflict between US, China, and respective allies

### Since 1945

**Post-WWII and Mao Era (1949-1970s)**

- WWII end led to creation of new world order
- 1949: China's civil war ended → creation of new domestic order
- **1949-1970s**: China strictly isolated communist country run by revolutionary leader **Mao Zedong** and chief administrator **Zhou Enlai**
- Slow recovery from WWII and civil war due to rigid, unproductive communist economic policies
- Policies didn't reward hard work, didn't allow savings/wealth creation
- Imposed draconian controls ensuring Mao and Communist Party remained in power
- Created isolation preventing China from benefiting from world offerings
- Typical Big Cycle pattern: political power winners suppress opposition via civil war to consolidate power (fear of overthrow)
- Chinese dynasties: secret and violent overthrows frequent, viewed as constant threat
- Went on throughout Mao's life
- Mao had many enemies: capitalists within China and Soviet Union (starting late 1950s) from outside
- **Marxist-Leninist communist dogmas** and isolation from "foreign devils" shaped China's 1949-76 actions
- China's development fell behind rest of world; much suffering, especially in Great Leap Forward and Cultural Revolution

**US-China Rapprochement (1970s)**

- Mao's greatest fear: Soviet Union (increasingly threatening in 1960s and especially 1970s)
- Adage: "the enemy of my enemy is my friend" → common enemy (Soviet Union) brought US and China together
- Led to visits to China by Henry Kissinger, then President Nixon
- Author heard firsthand about thinking and discussions from both Kissinger and Li Chaozhu (participants)
- Common enemy perspective top of mind for both sides in motivating "friendship" initiation (1972)

**Mao and Zhou died in 1976**

**Deng Xiaoping Era (1978 onwards)**

- **Deng Xiaoping came to power 1978**, changed just about everything with **"reform" and "open door" policies**
- Introduced **much freer, market-based economic system**
- Brought in foreign talent and capital to enable Chinese to seize new opportunities
- Distinguished move with statements like "to get rich is glorious"
- Asked about market-capitalist direction: "It doesn't matter whether a cat is black or white as long as it catches mice"
- Recognition that market-capitalist systems can "catch mice" (make riches)
- Best to get rich and powerful first, then work toward "common prosperity"
- **These policies led to huge economic advances that changed not just China but the whole world. China went from being a poor, weak country to being a very strong one that was more capitalist.**

**Author's Direct Experience (1984-present)**

- Saw changes up close from 1984 until now
- Through China contact, saw things through Chinese leaders' eyes as friends working on market/economy development
- Started going to China 1984 as guest of CITIC (only "window company" dealing with outside world in capitalist way)
- Asked to teach about world's capital markets
- China hardly had any money; author didn't go to make money or be involved with markets initially
- Went because curious; kept going because loves people and culture, could have good impact
- Invaluable education and enjoyment
- **Watched combination of powerful economic reform and opening up to outside world take China from:**

1. **Classic unproductive communist country** to
2. **Effective "socialist market economy"** to
3. **Development of capital markets and version of capitalism** to
4. **Forming of classic debt bubble** that led to
5. **Classic debt bust** (type where debt denominated in own currency, most debtors and creditors own citizens) to
6. **Classic great power conflict**

**China's Transformation Details**

- Classic upward swing in Big Cycle
- Took China's people from terrible poverty to much-improved living standards
- Many people and country as whole gained great riches and powers
- Big increases in debts and developments in capital markets created big wealth gaps and bubble
- **Author witnessed up close China go from grappling with poverty and geopolitical weaknesses to creating market/debt reform and open-door policies → great increases in riches and geopolitical power → grappling with greater wealth and geopolitical powers → big wealth/opportunity gaps and big domestic/international conflicts**

### The Deng Era: Big Cycle Unfolds

- China's inexpensive labor and high productivity gains provided world with attractively priced manufactured goods
- US and most of world liked getting attractively priced manufactured goods on good terms, especially because **China used money it earned to lend to Americans who bought the merchandise**
- China's income, wealth, and power increased greatly; **at same time, US overborrowed and started to decline**

**2008 Financial Crisis**

- US had big debt crisis putting China in position of uncertainty about whether large portion of debt assets would be paid back
- Questioning United States' financial strength
- Author was in midst of situation; Chinese side handled debt crisis with grace and understanding

**G20 Formation (2008)**

- **Group of 20 (G20) formed** to be more realistically representative group of powerful countries than G7 (given shifts in world power)
- First summit to deal with global financial crisis
- Agreed to be very stimulative
- China and virtually all countries increased credit available
- **Improved conditions, increased wealth gaps, raised debt levels relative to income levels**
- In US: widening wealth gaps and economic suffering of those left behind created change in sentiment
- Blamed China for job-loss problems
- Most adversely affected workers: non-college-educated men (Donald Trump later appealed to)
- **American companies complained not allowed to fairly compete in China and Chinese were stealing Americans' intellectual property**

**China's Growing Power and Assertiveness**

- China's skills and powers continued growing
- Gave China resources to develop military, geopolitical influence, technological powers
- **Led to becoming more assertive and seemingly threatening**
- 2009: pointing to old map demarcating South China Sea boundary, China asserted proper boundaries far beyond what other countries claimed
- 2016: Permanent Court of Arbitration ruled against China's claim; dispute continues today

**Xi Jinping Era (2012 onwards)**

- **President Xi Jinping and new leadership team came to power 2012**
- **Main goals: reform the economy and eliminate corruption**
- Author participated in discussions in third plenum (new government's big planning meeting after top people appointed)
- Very open and collaborative environment
- Key issues discussed, thoughts exchanged openly
- Quality of discussions about eliminating corruption and reforms: sincere and excellent
- Great desire and enthusiasm from new strong leaders to improve China
- **Reforming the economy meant modernizing it to be more market-driven**
- Example: five major banks lent money to state-owned enterprises implicitly guaranteed by government (had printing press)
- Little lending to small- and medium-size enterprises
- Leadership wanted to change that, develop capital markets improving access to borrowing, lending, investing
- Author closely involved, saw how responsible people thought about it and what they did
- For most of Xi's first five-year term: a) openness to outside thinking, b) strong desire to reform economy (more market-driven), c) strong action to eliminate corruption
- Senior leaders chosen were inclined to do those things
- How to do debated; some benefited, others hurt by changes → created divisions
- **After coming to power, Xi immediately purged strong rival (Bo Xilai) and moved strongly to eliminate corruption and reform economy**

**Consolidation of Power**

- Late in Xi's first term: **movement to consolidate political power around him via move to "core leadership"**
- If you think US politics brutal, should see politics in China
- Became most clear in leadership changes accompanying shift from first to second five-year term under Xi

**China's Remarkable Accomplishments**

- Up until then, remarkable accomplishments—**by many measures the greatest in human history**
- **Since author first started going to China in 1984: China's per capita income increased 20x, average life expectancy increased by 12 years, poverty rate fell from 81% to less than 1%**

**Russia-Ukraine and Xi's 2025 Plan (2014-2015)**

- **In 2014, Russia annexed Crimean Peninsula from Ukraine**
- Whole other story to be discussed another time
- Though Russians and Chinese had dislike and distrust for each other, drawn together by common enemy, saw symbiotic economic relationship possible
- **In 2015, Xi put out his 2025 plan** describing need for China to rise and dominate certain industries
- **Viewed as aspirational by Chinese and threatening by Americans**
- **China could no longer "hide power"**
- China became more threatening to other countries: grew in world trade, riches grew, asserted itself more geopolitically, "stole" intellectual property
- **Americans began to blame China for economic problems and viewed China as greater threat**

**Trump Era and Great Power Conflict (2017-2018)**

- **Due to middle-class job losses in US** (attributed to Chinese imports and China's greater assertiveness internationally), **pendulum of sentiment toward China swung from positive to negative**
- **When President Trump came to power in 2017 and President Xi began his second term in 2018, the great power conflict began in earnest**
- Started with trade negotiations evolving into tests of power and type of cold war
- Became clear to Chinese leaders that classic great power conflict was emerging
- Author assured by Chinese senior leader that Chinese leadership didn't want to change multilateral world order with respect to multinational organizations (UN, World Trade Organization, World Health Organization, World Bank, IMF)
- Senior leader argued changes to world order and threats to multilateralism were result of Trump administration's move toward unilateral, "America First" approach
- Put US interests ahead of global community's, made containing China top priority
- By this time, Russia and China increasingly viewed United States as common threat → became more aligned

**COVID and Convergence of Forces (2019-2020)**

- **Then in 2019-20, COVID emerged**
- Same time: China's debt bubble and wealth gaps grew, relations with US worsened
- Classic convergence of big debt/financial, internal order, external order, and acts of nature forces into risky mix
- Taiwan issue was (and still is) very big, contentious issue
- China expected One China unification promise delivered; instead seemed movement toward more independence
- Intensified because most advanced computer chips in world produced in Taiwan
- Whoever controls them controls most powerful technology in world
- Seeing all contentious domestic and international issues evolve, plus understanding of history, **led Xi to convey that there is a big 100-year storm on the horizon**

**Xi's Second Term and Consolidation (2018)**

- **In 2018, Xi began his second five-year term with more consolidated power** around him as head of core leadership
- Four of seven members of Standing Committee of Politburo as close allies
- 2020: much of China shut down due to COVID, raised internal ire about handling
- 2021 (bit more than halfway through Xi's second term): China's domestic debt bubble burst
- Xi emphasized importance of "common prosperity"
- Didn't like how rich business leaders were arrogantly seeking to exert influence over how China was run
- Government took seemingly arbitrary actions not consistent with type of rule of law and traditional property protections investors thought important
- Leadership knocked back some billionaire business leaders and their businesses to put them in place

**Xi's Third Term Shift (October 2022)**

- **At beginning of Xi's third term in October 2022, China's leadership shifted from reform-minded globalists to loyal, patriotic communists with tighter controls over possible opposition**
- **Shifted from being highly free-market-oriented with capital markets flourishing to being more Mao-like communist as internal conflict and international great power conflict intensified**

### China's Current Situation (March 2025)

China now experiencing:

1. Big debt crisis while also turning to more traditional communist economic policies
2. Increased internal conflict being eliminated by more strict, autocratic policies directed by president/chairman
3. Increased international conflict with United States and great changes in world
4. Climate change happening and likely to have big effect on China
5. Technology war that neither it nor United States can afford to lose
- Simultaneously making great advances in many areas, especially technology-enabled manufacturing (sells very inexpensively)
- Emerging countries (85% of world's population) are China's big new target market

**Second Trump Administration (March 2025)**

- At time of writing, second Trump administration recently came into power in US
- Has to deal with: 1) big debt issue, 2) internal conflict leading to employ more strict, semi-autocratic policies to overpower opposition and leftist policies, 3) increased international conflict with China and aligned countries, 4) climate change likely to have big effect, 5) technology war neither US nor China can afford to lose
- **Under-the-surface attacks on each other have been vicious**

**Great Power Squaring-Off**

- **Seeing squaring-off of these two great powers, along with allies lining up behind them and ideologies**
- **Looks a lot like what we saw in 1930s** when world was at similar stage in Big Cycle
- **Rapprochement of US toward China**: President Trump described Xi as "great leader" who "controls 1.4 billion people with an iron fist"
- What will happen in US and China and world will be test of relative strengths of these two great powers and their two very different approaches and systems
- Two great powers now in war that fortunately hasn't yet turned into military confrontation
- Shaping up to be greatest great power conflict ever
- Very senior Chinese leader explained how differently these two sides fight war
- Western countries follow Mediterranean approach to war (head-on)
- Chinese use much subtler, deceptive approach along lines of what was described in *The Art of War* by Sun Tzu (written ~2,500 years ago)
- Through many years and close China contacts, author learned about power of timeless principles affecting Chinese leaders' approaches to dealing with Chinese people and outside world

## China and the Five Big Forces

### Ultra-Brief Summary vs. Five Big Forces Template

**1. The debt/economic force**

- Led to China's debt rising relative to incomes (though not relative to liquid assets until 2009, coming out of global financial crisis)
- Then debt—especially local government, corporate, and real estate debt—started to grow into bubble that burst in 2021
- Began deleveraging
- Like Japan's, most of China's debt denominated in local currency, allowing it to engineer "beautiful deleveraging" (which Japan failed to do)
- Don't yet know whether China will manage well, though now appears China has been slow to deal with and is in late part of Big Debt Cycle most analogous to Japan in 1990s
- Same time: China has highly competitive innovative sectors not at all encumbered by debts

**2. The internal conflict and internal politics force**

- Led government to tighten controls
- Environment of more fear, slowed decision making, chilled economy, hurt capital and people flows
- Contributed to economic slowness in China
- Moved about halfway back toward Maoist-Marxist communist policies
- Chinese policies known to swing a lot as way of creating fear, cleaning things out, then rebuilding

**3. The external conflict force**

- Led to classic great power conflict with United States
- Hurt flows of trade, capital, and people
- Led to greater military preparation and risk

**4. The acts of nature force**

- Took form of COVID pandemic problem (late 2019 through 2022)
- Strained population's satisfaction for how leadership was handling it
- Contributed to government increasing controls
- China also used its remarkable inventiveness, government-directed economic policies, advanced manufacturing capabilities to make great strides in solar and wind power
- Become world's most cost-effective producer of these items
- Another story for another digression

**5. The technology force**

- Led both China and US to make advances in number of new technologies, most importantly in advanced AI
- China seemingly fallen behind US in development of most advanced chips
- Same time: excelling in inexpensive AI and advanced manufacturing, especially in robotics
- China very competitive in number of technology areas

### Summary

- In recent years, four out of five major forces (debt/economic, internal conflict, international conflict, acts of nature) have become increasingly threatening to China
- Fifth force (technology) appears to be mixed picture of great advances and falling behind and leaping ahead of US in different ways
- In Part IV, author will tell what he thinks about the future

## Appendix: China's Big Debt Cycle in a Few Charts

### China's Debt Picture Overview

- Charts paint China's debt picture
- Won't provide complete analysis with commentary (too much of digression)
- Not all debts properly accounted for, so charts meant to be broadly indicative
- China in part of Big Debt Cycle where non-central-government debt burdens have become excessive and problem
- Central government and central bank will have to help manage it
- Fortunately: most debt denominated in local currency, most debtors and creditors are domestic
- Central government and central bank have much greater ability to manage situation than if they weren't
- However: China's currency (renminbi) not widely held reserve currency, so not effective storehold of wealth
- Ideally: Chinese policy makers would have both ability and courage to swiftly engineer beautiful deleveraging
- However, such adjustments initially painful (cause great shifts in wealth)
- If not balanced properly, can just shift debt burdens, worsen long-term central government debt burdens, and/or severely undermine currency value (doing great damage to capital markets and through it to economy)
- **Japanese case and next chapter on it provide valuable lessons for Chinese policy makers** (as well as other policy makers, investors, businesspeople)
- China's debts reaching new highs even as economy is weaker than desired
- Same dynamic in Japan over recent decades as well

<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

### China's Debt Conclusion and Transition to Japan

- **China bond yields** show real yields around 0.5%, relatively unattractive in normal conditions but relatively attractive in a deflating economy with falling asset prices, and especially unattractive relative to US rates
- **Nominal government bond rates approaching zero** signal that "non-conventional" fiscal and monetary policies will need to be used
- **Inverted yield curve** (late February 2025) indicates cash is relatively attractive, creating a "pushing on a string" problem
- **Liquidity measures continue rising** (total social financing, money supply, loans from financial sector) without producing real economic rebound—another "pushing on a string" sign

> "While the debt issue is a big, important issue that could be a terrible burden for the Chinese economy as it was for the Japanese economy if Chinese policy makers don't handle it well—i.e., if the leaders don't engineer a beautiful deleveraging, which they have the ability to do because their debts are denominated in their own currency and most debtors and creditors are their own citizens. However, I want to reiterate that there are important non-debt-burdened parts of the economy that are innovating and flourishing that will certainly be viable both in and out of China in the years to come and that Chinese assets are now very cheap. Chinese policy makers would be well-served to read the next chapter on the Japanese case and the lessons it provides, as would the rest of us."

### Chinese Cultural and Philosophical Context

- **Da (big/grand) and tong (unity, harmony, coordination)** — ancient principle (time of Confucius) describing how good things should be shared by all, leadership should operate for public good rather than self-interest or group interest
- **Confucianism** — harmony through clear hierarchy and moral leadership; leaders put society's well-being ahead of self-interest; emphasizes education, meritocracy, quality relationships, international governance priorities (formed around 500 BCE)
- **Legalism** — strict rule of law and pragmatism over morality (formed around 250 BCE); running China as hierarchical empire
- **Chinese word "country"** = two characters: "state" + "family"
- Lesser influences: **Taoism** (harmony and nature of all things), **Buddhism** (harmony among people and all things)
- Author's perspective: Understanding these philosophical roots helps grasp leadership perspectives and system logic, including inclination toward Marxism (common prosperity, autocratic leadership, inflexibility to follow leader unless failure occurs)
- **Capitalism vs. other systems** — humanity has struggled with relative merits; Chinese approach differs from Western capitalism in core values (Christianity vs. Confucianism/legalism)
- **Big Cycle boom-bust pattern** has been consistent across different political/economic systems

