## Chapter 16: The Japanese Case and the Lessons It Provides

### Chapter Overview

> "This chapter shows how a heavily indebted reserve currency country, Japan, handled its debts with reference to the Big Cycle template. It shows the Big Debt Cycle transpiring in the very classic way, with the cause/effect relationships working as I described, but it is especially interesting because for more than two decades Japanese policy makers did the exact opposite of what should be done to execute a beautiful deleveraging—i.e., they did not restructure the debts for nine years and they didn't drive interest rates below inflation rates and nominal growth rates for 23 years."

- Case study gets technical but highlights can be read in ~10 minutes by following bold text
- Japan's story extends back to its Big Cycle prior to 1945; will summarize post-1945 and briefly cover pre-1945 context

### Before 1945

#### Early History and Foreign Contact

- **Japan had elevated civilization, happily isolated until foreign powers demanded "trade"** and threatened/exploited Japan
- Similar to **China's Century of Humiliation** — foreign powers collapsed Japan's internal order and world order
- **US Commodore Matthew Perry** arrived in 1853, led to fall of Japan's 250-year-old domestic order under **Tokugawa family shogunate**
- Foreign military superiority led to collapse of existing domestic and monetary orders, replaced by new ones

#### Meiji Era (1868) — Modernization

> "As the Japanese realized that the foreign, more modern approaches were better, the Japanese government was replaced by a new government in 1868, which largely copied the Western powers' approaches."

- **New domestic order**: constitutional monarchy with parliament and new emperor (**Meiji**)
- Modernization achieved by following Western styles for education, economy, military
- **Puccini's Madama Butterfly** dramatizes this era
- **Reform and opening led to Japan becoming a great power** — similar to China's later transformation under **Deng Xiaoping** (~100 years later)
- Defeated regional rivals: China (1894-95), Russia (1904-05); conquered/annexed Korea (1910)
- WWI: allied with British, took German territories in Asia and Chinese territories
- After WWI: given formal control of German territories and Shandong province in China

#### Democracy's Collapse (1912-1926)

- **From 1912 to 1926, Japan's domestic order was parliamentary democracy**
- **Economic problems led to classic combination**: debt/economic crisis + democracy dysfunction = collapse of public trust + hard-right takeover
- Rising nationalism, militarism, expansionism to secure economic resources and territory
- 1921: Prime minister assassinated by young nationalist
- 1929 crash led nationalist military to seize control
- Opponents treated as threats; laws silenced leftists and democratic activists (e.g., **1925 "Peace Preservation Law"**)

#### Path to WWII

> "The Great Depression made the economic situation worse and from 1937 to 1940 all political parties were dissolved, and there was increasing autocratic control that left the power exclusively in the hands of the military. In other words, events followed the classic script."

- **Geopolitically**: nationalistic, militaristic Japan invaded China's **Manchuria** (1931), then more of China (1937)
- Conflict with US led to trade sanctions similar to current US-China conflict
- **US, UK, Netherlands imposed export restrictions** that hurt Japanese economy and security by freezing Japanese assets and cutting off oil exports to Japan
- **Led to Pearl Harbor attack**, war with US
- **Japan lost WWII** due to US secretly inventing nuclear power
- **All Japanese money and debt destroyed**; Japan occupied and reconstructed by US (1945-1952)

### Total Debt-to-GDP Ratio Since 1870

- Chart shows Big Debt Cycle prior to 1945 and post-1945
- Big run-up in 1930-45 period before/during war
- Debt wipeout brought ratio to low levels until 1970
- Big debt bubble leading to 1989-90 bust
- Rise in ratio until recently
- **Short-term debt and economic cycles are imperceptible** when viewing Big Debt Cycles

### Since 1945

#### Rebuilding (1945-1990)

> "In brief, from 1945 through 1990, Japan rebuilt itself to become the second-greatest economic power in the world and in the process built up a huge debt burden that funded a bubble that burst in 1989-90, which has had a huge weakening effect on Japan ever since."

- Focus on post-1990 period (deleveraging part of Big Debt Cycle)
- Most relevant for understanding current US, China, Europe cases
- Won't cover 1945-90 expansion period

### The Big Debt Cycle Since 1990

#### What NOT to Do (1990-2013)

> "The Japanese government's handling of its debt problem from 1990 until 2013 exemplified exactly what not to do. It was the exact opposite of what I described should be done to execute a beautiful deleveraging even though Japan had the capacity to execute a beautiful deleveraging because almost all of its debt was denominated in its local currency and almost all of the difficult debtor-creditor relationships were between Japanese parties, plus it was a net creditor to the rest of the world."

- **Policy makers did not restructure debts** — debt burdens lingered on bank/company balance sheets, making them "zombie institutions"
- **Held to employment and cost policies** that were rigid, couldn't effectively cut costs and adapt
- **Did not make interest rates low relative to nominal growth and inflation** until deflation and near-zero rates in 1995
- **Did not meaningfully monetize debts** until after deflation and near-zero interest rates
- Nearly **two decades of insufficient fiscal/free-market policy adjustments and monetary stimulus**
- Result: **continuous deflation and economic stagnation** until mid-2013
- Companies and people didn't have financial conditions to get debt burden crisis behind them
- **Japanese government didn't deal with non-performing-loan problem until 1999** (nine years after bubble popped)
- Didn't monetize debt and bring interest rates significantly below nominal growth/inflation until 2013

#### Demographic Headwind

- **Japan's aging population**: 1990 had 12% over 65 and 69% working-age; now 29% over 65 and only 59% working-age

### "Three Arrows" Policy (Late 2012/Early 2013)

> "Fiscal and monetary policies changed greatly and appropriately when Bank of Japan Governor Kuroda and Prime Minister Abe came to power in late 2012/early 2013 and initiated their "three arrows" policy to 1) increase the money supply, 2) boost central government spending, and 3) enact economic and regulatory reforms to make the Japanese economy more competitive, which, as previously described, are classically the best policies to negate deflationary, depressionary forces."

- **2013-2019**: no deflation, low positive growth (0.9%/year), beginning of healing period
- **Deflationary and depressing psychological conditions lingered** after 23 years of debt depression
- Lasting negative effects on strength and vibrancy that characterized pre-1990 Japan

### Policy Details (2013+)

- **Extremely large debt monetization** and fiscal deficit stimulus (5% of GDP deficits on average)
- **BoJ bought massive amounts of Japanese yen debt** (now holds government bonds worth >90% of GDP)
- **Interest rates pushed 0.9% below nominal growth rate and 1% below inflation rate**
- **Yen depreciated** — all very stimulative
- **Combined lower interest rates + currency depreciation** = Japanese government bonds became terrible store of wealth: **lost 45% relative to US bonds and 60% relative to gold**
- Average interest rate ~2.2% below US rate
- Currency depreciated 5.5%/year in real terms vs. dollar
- **-45% cumulative return** on Japanese government bond almost entirely due to currency depreciation (lower carry/accrual offset by ~20% price gains from falling yields)
- **Japanese inflation averaged only 1.1%/year** vs. US inflation of 2.7%/year due to domestic deflationary pressures

> "The principle should resonate: don't own government bonds when there are extreme amounts of debt monetization."

#### Wage and Cost Competitiveness

- **Modest inflation of 0.8%/year in worker compensation** (yen terms) since 2013
- **Big yen depreciations + wage gains in other nations** made Japan more competitive
- **Total decline of 58% in cost of Japanese worker** relative to American worker since 2013
- **Other domestic items in Japan fell in cost** relative to other countries
- Both helped make Japan more competitive

### Debt Service Reduction

- **Japanese interest debt service fallen over 50%** (and over 65% since 2001)
- Much easier to service the debt despite increased debt levels

### Debt Monetization Impact

- **Japanese debt relative to economy increased by almost 10%**
- **To neutralize effects, BoJ bought over half of all government debt and absorbed debt service costs**, which it monetized
- Declines in interest rates engineered by BoJ contributed to debt relief
- More benefit occurred before Governor Kuroda (short rates already hit zero)

### Current Debt Metrics (2001 → 2013 → Today)

**Government Debt (% GDP)**
- 2001: 99%
- 2013: 197%
- Today: 215%
- Change: +9% (debt increased by ~10%)

**ex-CB Holdings**
- 2001: 93%
- 2013: 178%
- Today: 123%
- Change: -31% (CB monetized enough to push ex-CB debt down ~30%)

**Average Interest Rate on Govt Debt**
- 2001: 2.3%
- 2013: 0.9%
- Today: 0.6%
- Change: -40% (average interest rates fell 40%)

**ex-CB Govt Interest Service (% GDP)**
- 2001: 2.1%
- 2013: 1.7%
- Today: 0.7%
- Change: -56% (interest govt pays to public down >50%)

### Charts: Debt and Debt Service Trends

- Bottom-left chart: substantial declines in interest service actually paid by government to public
- Other charts: Japan got there through central bank purchases and large declines in interest and principal payments
- Massive debt increase concurrent with improvement in Japan's central government balance sheet
- **Net assets** (government assets minus liabilities) now 20% better in dollar terms vs. 2013
- BoJ accumulated dollar reserves (primarily 2001-12 period)
- Japan's debts in dollars not up as much due to yen depreciation

### Winners and Losers

> "Who were the winners and who were the losers? Clearly the big losers were the Japanese debt holders, including the Japanese central bank."

- **Japanese bond holders lost 6% in real terms** (real yields generally negative)
- **Lost 45% vs. US bonds, 60% vs. gold** if they held US bonds/gold instead
- Chart shows real return of holding JGBs as Japanese investor (in local currency) vs. US bonds and gold

### BoJ Balance Sheet Deterioration

- Big deterioration in BoJ's balance sheet
- **Losses will be very large if Japanese real and nominal bond yields rise** to more reasonable levels (e.g., 2% and 3%, respectively)

### Scenario: 3% Rise in Real Interest Rates

If Japan had 3% rise in real interest rates (from -0.3% to 2.7%):

- **BoJ would experience ~30% of GDP mark-to-market loss** on bond holdings and seriously negative cash flow (~-2.5% of GDP)
- **Government deficit would widen from ~4% of GDP to ~8% of GDP** over next 10 years due to interest cost increases (not including outlays to cover central bank losses)
- Government debt would surpass post-WWII peak, rising from 220% to 300% over next 20 years

> "The combined cash flow need across the central bank and the central government would be around 5-6% of GDP per year, which is huge."

- Would need to be handled through debt issuance, money printing, and/or deficit reduction
- If financed by central bank printing = equivalent of another QE round (money stock expansion), not including additional printing to offset private sector selling

> "Resolving it would require even greater write-downs in debt and devaluations of the currency—with the Japanese people becoming relatively poorer in the process—until Japan is competitive enough to begin a new cycle."

### Price Changes in Japan

- **Non-tradable goods** (local wages, services, housing) seen essentially no price increases in yen terms and significant deflation in global currency terms since 2000
- **Affordability of rent** (rent vs. wages) barely moved
- **Tradable goods and commodities way up** because of currency depreciation
- **Japanese workers more competitive than ever**

### Dollar Income Decline

- Japan has seen dramatically lower dollar incomes
- Purchases on imports much more expensive
- Dollar GDP per capita: individuals in Japan used to be richer than US individuals, now ~60% poorer
- Obvious to any Japanese person traveling abroad

### Inflation Composition Differences

> "Whereas total average inflation is similar across major categories, the composition of inflation is very different. In Japan, there has been deflation in non-tradables—housing and labor especially—while prices of tradable goods (i.e., things you can purchase from abroad like electronics, toys, oil, etc.) have soared with some key tradable commodities up more than 3x in yen terms."

- **Non-tradables flat** in price while **tradable commodities up 2-10x** (3x on average)

