### Graph Descriptions and Data Visualizations

**Description 49: Economic Cycles and Productivity Trends**
- Visual shows **productivity** as straight upward-sloping line (long-term growth)
- **Short-term debt cycles**: smaller, frequent waves overlaid on productivity trend
- **The Big Debt Cycle**: larger, overarching wave pattern
- Short-term cycles depicted as oscillations within the big debt cycle

**Description 50: US Private Debt (1900-2020)**
- Private debt as % of GDP tracked over 120 years
- Two major **deleveraging periods** marked: Great Depression (1930s) and post-2008
- General upward trend between these periods, peaking ~2008
- Shows century-long evolution of private sector borrowing behavior

**Description 51: US Central Government Debt (1900-2040)**
- Two major spikes: WWII (1940s) and post-2000s surge
- Projected 2040 levels: **exceeding 120% of GDP**
- Annotation: "The central government levering up" at 1940s spike
- Shows both historical trends and ominous future projections

**Description 52: Combined Government and Private Debt**
- **Blue line** (government): peaks 1940s, rises sharply after 2000, projected growth through 2040
- **Red line** (private): low until mid-20th century, peaks 2008, then stabilizes
- Private debt remained dominant through much of late 20th century
- Government debt now accelerating while private debt plateaus

**Description 53: Debt Service Components**
- Three lines: total debt service (blue), interest payments (green), principal payments (red)
- Debt service low 1900 to mid-20th century, sharp increase in 1940s
- Post-2020 projections show **steep increase in total debt service**
- Key annotation: "Rising principal payments; interest still low but projected to rise"
- Principal payments (red) becoming larger burden than interest

**Description 54: Bond Yields and Inflation (1945-2025)**
- **Red line** (inflation): peaks late 1940s and late 1970s, gradual decline after
- **Blue line** (bond yield): similar trend, peaks early 1980s before decreasing
- Both show slight upward trend in 2020s
- Demonstrates correlation between bond yields and inflation over time

**Description 55: Real Yield Data (1900-2030)**
- **Solid blue line**: actual real yield data
- **Dashed red line**: estimated real yield
- Horizontal dashed gray line: 2% reference level
- Yield oscillates around 2% (1900-1940s), sharp decline 1970s
- 1980s peak above 6%, then gradual decline into negative territory ~2010
- Recent rebound approaching 2% by 2030

**Description 56: Nominal Rate, Real Yields, and Breakeven Inflation**
- **Blue line** (nominal rate): significant fluctuations, peaks ~16% around 1980
- **Red line** (real yields): relatively stable, dips below 0% in 1970s and early 2020s
- **Gray line** (breakeven inflation): similar to nominal but less pronounced peaks
- Arrows highlight: sharp rise/fall of nominal rate around 1980 and gradual decline in rates over time

**Description 57: 3M Minus 10 Year Rate (Yield Curve)**
- **Blue line**: 3M Minus 10 Year Rate (left axis, -4% to 4%)
- **Red line**: 3M Divided by 10 Year Rate (right axis, 0% to 200%)
- Blue line fluctuates above/below 0%, indicating yield curve inversions
- Notable volatility during Great Depression, post-WWII, and recent cycles

**Description 58: Corporate Bond Spreads (1920-2020)**
- Red line tracks spread percentage (0% to 8%)
- Notable peaks: Great Depression (1930s), early 1980s, 2008 financial crisis
- Highlights periods of stability vs. volatility in corporate credit risk
- Spread reflects economic conditions and default risk over past century

**Description 59: Government Revenue Allocated to Debt Service (1900-2040)**
- Three lines: total debt service (blue), interest (green), principal (red)
- **1900-1940**: debt service rises sharply, peaking in 1940s
- **1940-1980**: fluctuates but remains relatively low
- **1980 onward**: begins rising with sharp projected increase after 2020
- Annotations: "Rising debt service" (early 20th century), "Rising principal payments; interest still low but projected to rise" (2020s)
- 2040 projections show significant increase, principal payments contributing most

**Description 60: Interest Rates and Monetary Base**
- **Blue line** (USA short-term interest rate, left axis): -2% to 18%
- **Red line** (USA monetary base as % of GDP, right axis): 0% to 30%
- Two periods labeled **"Big money printing"**: 1940s and 2008 onward
- During these periods, monetary base spikes while interest rates decline or stay low
- First spike (1940s) coincides with WWII, second (post-2008) continues into 2020s
- Visualizes relationship between monetary policy and interest rates

**Description 61: Central Bank Profit Scenarios**
- **Blue line** ("Reported"): stable ~0% of GDP, rises ~2008, peaks early 2020s, then negative
- **Red line** ("If Bonds Marked to Market"): similar but more pronounced fluctuations
- Red line diverges sharply downward early 2020s, reaching below -3% of GDP
- Shows hidden losses when bonds marked to market during crises

**Description 62: Government Debt Projections by Country (2000-2050)**
- Eight graphs: World, G7, US, China, Germany, Japan, UK, France, Italy
- **World**: 60% (2000) → 120% (2050)
- **G7**: 80% (2000) → ~200% (2050), sharp increase after 2025
- **US**: 60% (2000) → 200%+ (2050), sharp increase after 2025
- **China**: ~0% (2000) → 100%+ (2050)
- **Germany**: peaks ~80% (2010), declines to 40% (2050)
- **Japan**: 150% (2000) → 300%+ (2050), sharp increase after 2025
- **UK**: 50% (2000) → 150% (2050), sharp increase after 2025
- **France**: 50% (2000) → ~200% (2050), sharp increase after 2025
- **Italy**: 120% (2000) → 180%+ (2050)
- Vertical line marks transition from historical to forecasted data (~2025)

**Description 63: CPI and Interest Rates (1970-1982)**
- **Blue line** (Headline CPI): peaks ~14% around 1980
- **Red line** (USA Avg Interest Rate, average of 3M and 10-year): peaks ~16% in 1981
- Correlation visible between inflation and interest rates
- Both experience significant increases late 1970s/early 1980s, then decline

**Description 64: Yield Curve Metrics (1970-1982)**
- **Blue line** (3M Minus 10 year Rate, left axis): -6% to 6%
- **Red line** (3M Divided by 10 year Rate, right axis): 40% to 160%
- Fluctuations with dips below 0% mid-1970s and early 1980s (yield curve inversions)
- Indicates periods of economic stress during stagflation era

**Description 65: USA Estimated Real Bond Yield (1970-1982)**
- Red line shows estimated real bond yield
- Dashed line at 2% as reference
- Downward trend in 1970s, reaching very low levels late 1970s
- Sharp increase to very high real rates early 1980s (Volcker shock)

**Description 66: Real Interest Rate Measures (1970-1982)**
- **Blue line**: USA Avg Interest Rate Minus Headline Inflation
- **Red line**: USA Avg Interest Rate Minus GDP Deflator
- **Green line**: Average ("Avg")
- Blue and red lines fluctuate, crossing 0%, indicating positive/negative real rates
- Green line relatively stable
- Sharp dip mid-1970s, significant rise early 1980s, peaking 1981-1982

**Description 67: Labor's Share of Private Earnings (1930-1980)**
- Red line shows upward trend
- Steady increase from 1940s to late 1970s
- Peaks near 75% in late 1970s
- Lowest point just above 60% in early 1930s
- Black arrow points upward indicating rising trend

**Description 68: CPI, Interest Rate Spread, and Average Rate**
- **Blue line**: Headline CPI
- **Green line**: 3-month minus 10-year interest rate difference
- **Red line**: average USA interest rate
- Two peaks late 1970s/early 1980s where inflation and interest rates surged
- **Paul Volcker** appointment as Fed Chair marked, coinciding with sharp interest rate rise
- Circles emphasize peaks showing significant economic events

**Description 69: CPI and Interest Rates (1970-1990)**
- **Blue line**: Headline CPI (inflation measure)
- **Red line**: USA Avg Interest Rate (average of 3-month and 10-year)
- Significant rise in both late 1970s, peaking ~1980
- Both decline steadily afterward, red line remaining above blue throughout
- Black arrow points downward from 1980 peak

**Description 70: Yield Curve (1970-1990)**
- **Blue line** (3M Minus 10 year Rate, left axis): -6% to 6%
- **Red line** (3M Divided by 10 year Rate, right axis): 40% to 160%
- Fluctuates above/below 0%, indicating yield curve inversions and steepening
- Red line on different scale, reflecting ratio of short-term to long-term rates

**Description 71: Interest Rates, Inflation, and Bond Yield (1970-1990)**
- **Blue line**: USA Avg Interest Rate Minus Headline Inflation
- **Red line**: 3M Minus 10 year Rate
- **Green line**: USA Real Bond Yield
- Shows difference between average rates and inflation
- Red line tracks yield curve inversion
- Green line represents real bond yields
- Interplay with notable spikes/dips around late 1970s and early 1980

**Description 72: USA Real Bond Yield (1970-1990)**
- Red line represents real bond yield percentage
- Notable peaks early 1980s reaching above 6%
- Gradual decline toward 1990s
