**Description 76: USA Interest Rates and Inflation (1970-2010)**
- **Red line**: U.S. average interest rate
- **Blue line**: headline CPI inflation rate
- Peak in both ~1980, followed by steady decline
- By 2008, short-term interest rates hit 0%

**Description 77: Fed Balance Sheet (percent GDP)**
- Red line shows Federal Reserve's total assets as % of GDP
- Relatively flat until 2008, then spikes sharply
- Indicates Fed's "money printing" and debt-buying during financial crisis

**Description 78: Yield Curve (3-month vs 10-year Treasury)**
- **Blue line**: 3-month Treasury rate minus 10-year rate (-6% to 6%)
- **Red line**: 3-month divided by 10-year rate (0% to 200%)
- Yield curve fluctuates with notable inversions (negative values) before recessions
- By 2008, reflects "very easy money" as short-term rates hit 0%
- Annotations mark: "Short Rates Hit 0 percent" and "Money printing and buying debt by Federal Reserve begins"

**Description 79: USA Real Yield (1970-2010)**
- **Solid red line**: actual real yield
- **Dashed red line**: estimated real yield
- Annotations: "Short rates hit zero; liquidity squeeze causes real yields to briefly spike" and "Very easy money" near 2008
- General decline in real yields over time, fluctuations and sharp dip around 2008

**Description 80: Interest Rates Adjusted for Inflation**
- **Blue line**: USA Avg Interest Rate Minus Headline Inflation
- **Red line**: USA Avg Interest Rate Minus GDP Deflator
- Dashed gray line at 2% as reference
- Significant volatility, both lines frequently crossing above/below 2%
- Reflects changes in monetary policy and economic conditions

**Description 81: USA Monetary Base (2008-2020)**
- Red line shows monetary base as % of GDP (0% to 30%)
- Two significant increases circled: ~2008 (5% → 15%) and ~2020 (15% → 25%+)
- Visualizes quantitative easing and money printing episodes

**Description 82: USA Debt Levels and Debt Service (1945-2025)**
- **Left graph** (USA Debt Levels, percent GDP): blue (central government), red (private)
- Blue starts low 1945, increases after 1980, rises sharply after 2008
- Red starts higher, peaks ~2008, then declines slightly
- **Right graph** (USA Central Govt Debt Service, percent Revenue): blue (total), red (principal), green (interest)
- Blue fluctuates significantly, peaks ~1985 and 2025
- Red follows similar pattern at lower level
- Green remains relatively flat and low throughout

**Description 83: Interest Rates, Monetary Base, and Central Bank Profit (1945-2025)**
- **Left graph** (Interest Rates and Monetary Base): blue (short-term rate), red (monetary base % GDP)
- Blue peaks ~1980, declines thereafter
- Red stable until 2008, then rises sharply, peaking ~2020
- **Right graph** (Central Bank Profit, percent GDP): blue ("Reported"), red ("If Bonds Marked to Market")
- Blue stable until sharp decline ~2020, dipping below zero
- Red shows similar trend but more pronounced fluctuations during crises

**Description 84: USA Interest Rates, Bond Yields, and Real Yields (1945-2025)**
- **Top Left** (Interest Rates and Inflation): red (avg interest rate), blue (CPI)
- Peaks ~1980s, fluctuations before/after
- **Top Right** (USA Interest Rates): blue (10-year bond yield), red (short rate)
- Red shows sharper spikes vs blue, particularly 1980s
- **Bottom** (Real Bond Yield): blue (actual), red (estimated)
- Horizontal dashed line at 2% benchmark
- Text explains 2% real bond yield as benchmark, higher = expensive money, lower = cheap money

**Description 85: Yield Curves and Bond Yields (1945-2025)**
- **Left graph**: blue (3M Minus 10 year Rate, -2% to 4%), red (3M Divided by 10 Year Rate, 0% to 200%)
- Significant volatility, peaks/troughs around 1980 and 2020
- **Right graph**: blue (USA 10 year Bond Yield, peaks ~16% in 1980s), red (USA Inflation Rate in Bonds), green (USA Real Bond Yield, -4% to 8%)
- Green fluctuates between -4% and 8%
- Sharp peak 1980s, gradual decline in subsequent decades

**Description 86: Labor Share and Income Distribution (1945-2025)**
- **Left graph** (USA Labor Share of Private Earnings): 58% to 76%
- Rise 1945 to mid-1960s (peaks ~74%), steady decline to ~68% in recent years
- **Right graph** (USA Income Share): red (bottom 60%), blue (top 40%)
- Red (bottom 60%): gradual decline from ~46% (1980) to ~43% (recent)
- Blue (top 40%): increase from ~54% (1980) to ~57% (recent)
- Highlights trends in economic inequality and labor's share of earnings

**Description 87: Wealth and Income Distribution by Education (1990-2020)**
- **Left graph** (USA Wealth Share): blue (college-educated), red (non-college-educated)
- 1990: non-college >70%, college <30%
- Lines cross ~2000
- 2020: college >70%, non-college <30%
- **Right graph** (USA Income Share): blue (college), red (non-college)
- 1990: non-college ~60%, college ~40%
- Lines cross ~2010
- 2020: college ~60%, non-college ~40%
- Significant shift in wealth and income distribution favoring college-educated

**Description 88: China's Relative Power (600-2000)**
- X-axis: time 600-2000
- Y-axis: China's relative standing (1 = all-time maximum)
- Red line fluctuates, indicating China's relative power
- Key periods labeled: Tang, Song, Yuan, Ming, Qing Dynasties, PRC
- Gray vertical bars mark major wars (coincide with dips/changes)
- Peaks during Tang and Song, declines during Yuan, fluctuations during Ming and Qing
- Sharp rise in modern PRC era

**Description 89: China Debt Levels (1865-2025)**
- Three segments:
- **Pre-1937** (dashed red): estimate shows sharp rise early 20th century, peaking ~1925
- **1950-1980** (gray): rough estimate, low and stable
- Note: "PRC repudiates previous debts"
- **1980-2025** (solid red): steep continuous increase, particularly after 2000, reaching nearly 300% of GDP by 2025

**Description 90: Country Power Indices and US-China Conflict Gauge**
- **First graph** (Country Power Indices): China (red), USA (blue), 1800-2020
- China high 1800, declines sharply until mid-20th century, rises steeply after 2000
- USA low 1800, rises steadily to peak ~1950, then gradual decline
- **Second graph** (US-China Conflict Gauge): 1960-2020
- Red line shows generally increasing trend, notable spikes ~1990 and after 2000, highest near 2020
- Indicates growing conflict level over time

**Description 91: China Debt Levels by Sector**
- **First graph**: government (blue), non-financial businesses and LGFVs (red), households (green)
- Red rises sharply after 2000, surpassing 150% of GDP by 2024
- Blue and green also increase steadily, government approaching 80% by 2024
- **Second graph** (China Private Debt Level): combines household and non-financial business debt (including LGFVs)
- Rises steeply after 2000, exceeding 200% of GDP by 2024
- Indicates significant growth in private debt

**Description 92: China Government Debt and Debt Service**
- **Third graph** (China General Government Debt Level, percent GDP, Est Pre-1981): blue line shows steady increase starting 1980s, reaching nearly 90% by 2024 (red projection line)
- **Fourth graph** (China General Government Debt Service, percent Revenue with Projections): total (blue), interest (red), principal (green)
- Total rises sharply after 2000, projections show exceeding 100% of revenue by 2024
- Green (principal) accounts for majority of increase
- Red (interest) remains relatively stable
- Highlights rapid growth of debt across sectors, projections indicating continued increases through 2024

**Description 93: China Interest Rates and Yields**
- **Top Left**: China's 10-year bond yield (blue), year-over-year inflation (red), 3-year moving average of inflation (green), 1960-2020
- Bond yield and inflation show significant fluctuations, inflation peaking sharply late 1980s, stabilizing in recent years
- **Top Right** (China Real Yield): estimated real yield (red line), 1960-2020
- Real yield remains mostly below 2%, notable declines in recent decades
- **Bottom** (China Estimated Rates): nominal rate (blue), real yield estimate (red), breakeven inflation estimate (gray), 1960-2020
- Nominal rate consistently higher than real yield, both trending downward in recent years

**Description 94: China Short-Term Interest Rate and Yield Curve**
- **First graph** (China Short-Term Interest Rate): line graph, 0% to 16%
- Peaked ~1995, generally declined since, reaching below 4% in recent years
- **Second graph** (Yield Curve): 3-month minus 10-year rate (blue), 3-month divided by 10-year rate (red)
- Blue ranges -3% to 2%, red ranges 20% to 145%
- Yield curve fluctuates with notable inversions (negative values) around 2000 and 2020

**Description 95: China Financial Indicators as % of GDP**
- Four lines: **Total Social Financing** (blue, surpassing 300% by 2020), **M2** (red, reaching ~200%), **Loans in RMB from financial institutions** (gray, nearing 200%), **M0** (green, staying below 20%)
- All show upward trends, with Total Social Financing growing most dramatically

**Description 96: Government Debt Historical and Projected (1870-2030)**
- Red line indicates government debt levels over time
- Low until 1930s, spikes sharply ~1945, drops significantly post-war
- From 1970s onward, rises steadily, reaching over 250% of GDP by 2020
- Dotted lines for projections: gray (1990 IMF), green (2024 IMF)
- Shows historical patterns and ominous future trajectory

**Description 97: USA vs Japan Typical Wages in USD (1980-2025)**
- **Red line**: USA Typical Wage in USD (steady upward trend, reaching ~80K by 2025)
- **Blue line**: JPN Typical Wage in USD (rises sharply 1980-mid-1990s, peaks ~1995, then fluctuates downward, reaching ~30K by 2025)
- Highlights divergence: USA wages increasing consistently while Japan's decline after mid-1990s

**Description 98: Japanese Wages and Exchange Rate (1980-2025)**
- **Blue line**: Japanese typical wages in JPY (steady increase 1980-mid-1990s, plateau and slight upward trend after 2015)
- **Red line**: JPY to USD exchange rate (fluctuates significantly, peaking mid-1990s, declining sharply after 2012, continuing downward through 2025)
- Arrows indicate upward wage trend and downward exchange rate trend

**Description 99: Japan Government Debt Levels and Debt Service**
- **First graph** (Japan Government Debt Level): total (red line), excluding central bank holdings (blue line)
- Red rises steadily, surpassing 200% by 2013 (start of "Abenomics"), continues increasing
- Blue diverges downward after 2013 (debt held outside central bank reduced)
- **Second graph** (Japan Government Debt Service): total (red), excluding central bank holdings (blue)
- Both rise sharply until mid-1990s, peaking ~30% of GDP, then decline significantly
- Blue drops more steeply after 2013, reflecting reduced debt service costs for non-central bank holdings

**Description 100: Japan Public Debt Service Components**
- **First chart**: principal payments (blue), interest payments (red)
- Principal rises sharply in 1990s, declines after 2010
- Interest remains relatively low and stable throughout
- Falling debt burden attributed to longer debt issuance and lower interest rates
- **Second graph** (Debt Service Payments as % of Government Debt): steady decline from over 24% (1980s) to below 10% by 2025
- Decline attributed to combination of lower interest rates and smaller principal payments
- Highlights impact of economic policies and market conditions on Japan's debt trends

**Description 101: Japan 10-Year Bond Performance (2014-2024)**
- Three scenarios: local currency (real terms), unhedged vs USA bond, vs gold
- **Red line** (local currency real terms): steady decline from 0% (2014) to approximately -40% (2024)
- **Green line** (unhedged vs USA bonds): declines significantly, reaching around -60% by 2024
- **Blue line** (vs gold): remains relatively stable near 0% throughout
- Highlights underperformance of Japan's 10-year bond in real terms and against benchmarks over decade

**Description 102: Bank of Japan Scenarios and Government Deficit**
- **First graph** (BOJ MTM Bond Losses, percent GDP): 2005-2030
- Red line represents scenario where interest rates rise by 3%
- Moderate real rate increase would result in significant losses for BoJ
- Red dot at end shows sharp drop to nearly -30% of GDP
- **Second graph** (Japan Government Deficit, percent GDP): 1875-2050
- Compares current pricing scenario (green dot) with impact of 3% rise in yields (red dot)
- Red line shows sustained rise in yields would lead to large government deficits
- Potentially putting Japan on path toward debt spiral
- Highlights historical fluctuations and projects worsening trend under 3% yield rise scenario

<!-- pp. 381-396 -->

### Japan Case Study - Data Visualizations

**Description 105: Japanese Earnings Across Three Units (JPY, USD, Gold)**
- Three graphs measuring earnings in different units from 1980-2020
- **JPY graph**: Sharp rise in late 1980s marked as "bubble," peaking ~1990, followed by "bust" decline, stabilizing in 2000s-2010s
- **USD graph**: Similar bubble-bust pattern with steep increase in late 1980s, significant decline continuing into 2020s
- **Gold graph**: Sharp rise in late 1980s bubble, steep decline in bust, reaching lowest levels in 2000s-2010s
- Illustrates how currency measurement affects perceived earnings trends

**Description 106: Japanese Housing Costs**
- Left graph: Rent in thousands of JPY (200-280 range, 2000-2020)
  - Mild deflation in housing costs: peak ~2005, decline until 2010, gradual increase after 2020
- Right graph: Rent as proportion of typical monthly wage (0.6-1.0 range)
  - Little change in apartment affordability over years, remaining relatively stable

**Description 107: Cost of Living in Japan (Hours of Typical Wage)**
- Left graph: **Convenience store boxed lunch** cost in hours of typical wage
  - Sharp decline from 1980 to early 2000s (labeled "Bubble" and "Bust")
  - Gradual increase after 2010, reaching ~0.30 hours by 2020
- Right graph: **Cost of domestic motor vehicle** in months of typical wage
  - Relatively stable until early 2000s
  - Steady increase after, peaking ~11 months in 2020s
  - Note: "Post-2000 domestic autos up somewhat"

**Description 108: Theme Park Admission Fees**
- Left graph: Admission fee in USD (15-85 range, 1980-2020)
  - Significant increase over time with fluctuations
- Right graph: Admission as fraction of typical wage (days of work, 0.20-0.60 range)
  - Upward trend showing cost increased relative to wages, particularly after 2000

**Description 109: Private vs Government Debt in Japan**
- Left axis: Non-financial private debt (100-180% range)
- Right axis: Government debt (50-250% range), 1970-2020
- **Blue line (private debt)**: Rises sharply from 1970, peaking ~1990 at ~180% of GDP, declining steadily to ~140% by 2020
- **Red line (government debt)**: Low in 1970, gradually increases, accelerates after 1990, surpassing 200% of GDP by 2020
- Annotation highlights **inverse relationship**: "Government debt rises as private sector debt falls"
- Crossing point around 2010

**Description 110: Japan's Debt Service Reduction (2013-2023)**
- Debt service as % of GDP: decreased 11% (26% in 2013 to 15% in 2023)
- Debt service in yen: reduced 7% (128 trillion to 85 trillion yen)
- Ex-central bank government debt: decreased 3% (898 trillion to 748 trillion yen)
- Total government debt: increased 6% (997 trillion to 1,270 trillion yen)
- Central bank holdings: decreased 9% (99 trillion to 522 trillion yen)
- GDP in yen increased 4% (571 trillion to 583 trillion), with 2% decrease in both price level and real GDP
- Key mechanism: **Central bank balance sheet expansion offsetting government debt + lower interest rates + longer-maturity issuance** = reduced debt service costs

**Description 111: Bank of Japan Bond Holdings vs Real Yields**
- Blue line: BoJ bond holdings as % of GDP (left axis, 0-100%)
  - Near 0% in 1975, low until mid-1990s, rises sharply after 2010, reaching nearly 100% by 2025
- Red line: 10-year real yield (right axis, -1% to 5%)
  - Starts ~4% in 1975, fluctuates until mid-1990s, trends downward, negative values after 2015
- **Inverse relationship**: As BoJ bond holdings increase, real yields decrease

**Description 112: BoJ Bond Holdings vs Real Exchange Rate**
- Blue line: BoJ bond holdings—steady increase, particularly after 2010, reaching nearly 100% of GDP by 2025
- Red line: Real exchange rate—fluctuates significantly, sharp declines after 2015, reaching approximately -30% by 2025
- **Inverse relationship** highlighted in recent years

**Description 113: Japan vs USA Investment Returns**
- Left graph: "Japan vs USA Unhedged Bond Diff" (cumulative returns indexed to 2001, 1950-2025)
  - Rise sharply 1950-1980, fluctuate until 2000, then decline steeply to approximately -75% by 2025
- Right graph: "Japan vs USA FX Returns" (2000-2025)
  - Starts near 0% in 2000, rises slightly, then declines steadily to approximately -75% by 2025
- Both show consistent downward trajectory

**Description 114: Japan Debt Levels (JPY and USD)**
- Left graph: Debt in trillions of JPY (0-1400 range, 1975-2025)
  - Steady increase, sharp rise starting ~1995, continuing upward through 2025
- Right graph: Debt in trillions of USD (0-14 range, 1975-2025)
  - Similar trend but more fluctuations
  - Sharp rise from mid-1990s, peaking ~2015, slight decline but remaining high through 2025

**Description 115: Debt Changes by Currency (2001-2023)**
- **Total Debt (USD)**: 30% increase (4.3 trillion to 5.6 trillion USD)
  - Subcategory JPY change: 48% increase
  - Spot vs USD change: 12% decrease
- **Debt Service (USD)**: 16% decrease (0.8 trillion to 0.6 trillion USD)
  - JPY subcategory: 4% decrease
  - Spot vs USD: 12% decrease
- **Total Debt (Gold)**: 82% decrease (16 billion to 3 billion)
  - JPY subcategory: 48% increase
  - Spot vs Gold: 88% decrease
- Note: Debt and debt service in **foreign FX and gold have fallen**; sub-components are multiplicative, summing geometrically

**Description 116: Japan 10-Year Real Returns**
- Left graph: "Japan 10yr Cumulative Real Return" (indexed to 2001, 1980-2020)
  - Trends upward 1980-2020, peaking ~25%
  - Annotation: "JPN hedged bond returns have been decent since 2001, with notable worsening since COVID-era inflation"
- Right graph: "Japan 10 year Real Returns in USD" (1980-2020)
  - Fluctuates significantly, peaking ~50% in early 2000s
  - Steep decline after 2013, reaching approximately -50% by 2020
  - Annotation: "However, JPN bond returns have been very poor in USD terms, especially since 2013"

**Description 117: Import Prices vs Domestic CPI**
- Years 2000-2020, percentage changes (-20% to 20% range)
- **Red line (import prices)**: Significant fluctuations—sharp declines ~2008 and 2015, steep rise after 2020, peaking near 20%
- **Blue line (CPI)**: Relatively stable, hovering around 0% with slight increases after 2020
- **Green line (services CPI)**: Steady, gradual upward trend after 2020
- Annotations explain: "Import prices rose as the yen devalued, but that was offset by low domestic price growth (like services CPI)"
- "Tradables/imports rose in price; domestic goods stayed steady, keeping a lid on domestic inflation"
- Highlights **contrast between volatile import prices and stable domestic price indicators**

**Description 118: Japan Economic Indicators in USD**
- **Top Left (Home Prices in USD)**: Indexed to 2001, 1980-2020
  - Sharp rise in late 1980s, significant decline after 1990
  - By 2020, home prices in USD have fallen considerably
- **Top Right (Productivity-Adjusted Wages in USD)**: Indexed to 2001
  - Peaked in late 1980s/early 1990s, steady decline
  - By 2020, wages have dropped significantly, mirroring home prices trend
- **Bottom (FDI Inflows as % of GDP)**: 1990-2003, -0.25% to 1.00% range
  - FDI inflows remained low until ~2013, then began to increase
  - Note: While FDI levels still low, upward trend suggests **Japan has become more competitive**

**Description 119: Forward P/E Ratios**
- Graph spans 1990-2020
- Japan's line notably higher in early 1990s, peaking around 70, then declining and stabilizing closer to other countries
- Annotation: Starting in 2013, **equities in U.S. began cheapening relative to other developed countries**, but trend has reversed in recent years

**Description 120: FWD P/E Ratios (2008-2024)**
- Label marks "Start of QE" (quantitative easing) around 2008
- **U.S. line**: Significant rise in late 2010s, peaking above 25
- Other countries remain relatively stable or slightly lower

**Description 121: Japan Government Debt History (1900-2030)**
- Black line: Historical government debt levels, 0-300% of GDP range
- Sharp peak around 1945, followed by steep decline after **Japan effectively defaulted on wartime debt**
- After 1950, debt remains low until 1990s, then rises steadily, surpassing 200% of GDP by 2010
- By 2020, debt reaches approximately 250% of GDP
- Two dotted projection lines:
  - 1990 IMF projection (underestimated rise in debt)
  - 2024 IMF projection (predicts slight decline after 2024)
- Shaded vertical bands: Pink (recessions), gray (major wars)
- Annotation: "JPN effectively defaults on wartime debt" marked near sharp 1945 decline

**Description 122: Government Revenue Allocated to Debt Service (1900-2030)**
- Three main lines: Blue (total debt service), red (principal), green (interest)
- Dashed lines indicate forward projections for 1990 and 2024
- From 1900 to mid-20th century: sharp peaks, particularly around 1940s where **total debt service exceeds 350% of revenue**
- After 1950: percentages drop significantly, remain stable until 1980s
- From 1990s onward: total debt service gradually increases, peaking around 200% of revenue before stabilizing
- 2024 projections suggest slight decline

**Description 123: Japan Bond Yield and Inflation**
- Chart 1: **JPN 10Yr Bond Yield and Inflation**
  - Blue line (bond yield): Fluctuates significantly 1950s-1980s, peaking ~16% in 1970s, declining steadily to near 0% by 2020
  - Red line (inflation, 3-year moving average): Similar trend, remains below bond yield most of period, dipping negative after 1990
- Chart 2: **Japan Real Yield**
  - Blue line (real yield) and dashed red line (estimated real yield)
  - Real yield peaks in 1950s and 1970s, reaching above 6%, trends downward over time, turning negative after 2000

**Description 124: Japan Interest Rates - Estimated and Actual**
- Chart displays: Nominal rates (blue), real yields (red), breakeven inflation (BEI, gray)
- Nominal rates and real yields follow similar downward trajectory, starting high in 1950s, approaching 0% by 2020
- BEI remains relatively stable but trends slightly downward
- Chart 4: **Japan Short-Term Interest Rate and Monetary Base**
  - Blue line (interest rate): Starts high in 1950s, fluctuates, declines to negative levels by 2020
  - Red line (monetary base as % of GDP): Remains low until 1990s, then rises sharply, exceeding 120% of GDP by 2020

**Description 125: Japan Yield Curve and Corporate Spreads**
- Left graph: **Japan Yield Curve**
  - Blue line ("3 M Minus 10 Year"): Fluctuates around 0%, notable dips below -4%, peaks above 4%
  - Red line ("3 M Divided by 10 Year"): More dramatic fluctuations, peaking near 200%
- Right graph: **Japan BAA Corporate Spreads**
  - Red line: Remains relatively low and stable most of timeline
  - Sharp spike above 3% around 2008 financial crisis before returning to lower levels

**Description 126: Central Bank Profit as % of GDP**
- Years 1950-2020, -1.2% to 0.8% of GDP range
- Line starts near 0% in 1950, dips sharply below -1% in early 1950s
- Fluctuates between positive and negative values over decades
- Notable peaks around late 1980s and early 2010s, with profits reaching close to 0.8% of GDP
- Most recent data shows decline from peak in 2010s but remains above 0%

**Description 127: US Government Risk Gauges**
- Left graph: **Long-term government risk gauge** (1900-2020, 0-100%)
  - Fluctuating risk levels over time
  - Red dot at top right: current reading of **100%**
- Right graph: **Short-term government risk gauge**
  - Red dot at bottom right: current reading of **0%**
- Light gray shading represents historical risk levels
- Visual comparison of risk trends for long-term vs short-term government investments

**Description 128: USA Central Bank Risk Gauges**
- Left graph: **USA Central Bank Long-Term Risk Gauge** (1900-present, 0-100%)
  - Shaded area shows historical fluctuations
  - Red dot marks current reading at **46%**, slightly below 50%
- Right graph: **USA Central Bank Short-Term Risk Gauge** (1925-present, 0-100%)
  - Shaded area shows sporadic spikes over time, most of graph near 0%
  - Red dot at bottom: current reading of **0%**

**Description 129: US Debt Level Projections (1960-2030)**
- Years 1960-2030, debt as % of government revenue (0-800%)
- **Red line ("Current Path CBO")**: Rises sharply after 2000, continues increasing through 2030
- **Dashed green line ("3 percent Plan")**: Diverges from red line around 2025, showing slower increase
- Highlights difference between scenarios: "3 percent Plan" projects more controlled debt trajectory vs "Current Path (CBO)"

**Description 130: US Debt Scenarios with Fiscal Plans (1960-2030)**
- Similar to Description 129, debt as % of revenue (0-800%)
- **Red line ("Current Path CBO")**: Sharp rise after 2000, continues through 2030
- Two alternative fiscal plans (dashed lines):
  - **Green ("3 percent Plan")**: Gradual decline in debt levels starting ~2025
  - **Blue ("3 percent Plan (Phased In over 3 Yrs)")**: More gradual decline starting slightly later

**Description 131: US Federal Budget Breakdown**
- **Mandatory spending**: 61% of budget (4.3 trillion dollars)
  - Social Security: 1.6 trillion (22%)
  - Medicare: 1.1 trillion (16%)
  - Medicaid: 666 billion (9%)
  - Other mandatory programs: 898 billion (13%)
- **Discretionary spending**: 26% (1.8 trillion dollars)
  - Defense: 862 billion (12%)
  - Non-defense programs: 878 billion (12%)
  - Education: 83 billion (1%)
- **Net Interest** on debt: 13% (1 trillion dollars)
- Discretionary section highlighted in pink

**Description 132: Government Debt-to-Income Scenarios (CBO Analysis)**
- Grid analyzing debt-to-income ratios under various scenarios
- Current debt-to-income ratio: **583%**, baseline primary deficit: **12% of income** (CBO projection)
- Vertical axis: percentage changes in government income (-6% to 6%)
- Horizontal axis: percentage changes in government spending (-6% to 6% GDP terms)
- Each cell contains debt-to-income ratio under corresponding scenario
- Central cell (red box): **723%** representing current CBO path
- Higher ratios in darker shades
- Shows assumptions and baseline conditions for analysis

**Description 133: Debt-to-Income Impact Analysis (20-Year Projection)**
- Current debt-to-income ratio: **583%**, baseline primary deficit: **12% of income** (CBO)
- Grid with rows (government income changes, 6% to -6%) and columns (government spending changes, 6% to -6%)
- Example scenarios:
  - At 6% income and 6% spending: debt-to-income ratio = **831%**
  - At -6% income and -6% spending: ratio = **405%**
- Ratios decrease as government spending and income increase
- Highlights relationship between **fiscal policy adjustments and long-term debt sustainability**

**Description 134: Fiscal Policy Impact on Debt Ratios**
- Similar grid structure analyzing debt-to-income over 20 years
- Current debt-to-income ratio: **583%**, baseline primary deficit: **12% of income** (CBO)
- X-axis: government spending changes in % GDP terms (6% to -6%)
- Y-axis: government income changes in % terms (6% to -6%)
- Values range from **725%** (highest) to **334%** (lowest)
- Shows how different combinations of spending and income changes affect debt-to-income ratio
- **Higher spending and lower income** → higher ratios; **vice versa** → lower ratios

**Description 135: G7 Average Debt Trends**
- Left graph: **G7 Average Total Debt (percent GDP, Non-Financial)** (1900-2020+)
  - Red line: Historical data starts below 30% in 1900, fluctuates through 20th century, rises sharply after 1980, peaking near 280% by 2020
  - Dashed blue line: Projected increase beyond 2020
- Right graph: **G7 Average Total Debt Service (percent GDP, Non-Financial)** (same period)
  - Red line: Starts below 10% in 1900, rises and falls through 20th century, increases significantly after 1980, stabilizing around 40% by 2020
  - Dashed blue line: Projected upward trend beyond 2020

**Description 136: US Political Polarization (1900-2020)**
- Y-axis: Ideological positions (more conservative = positive, less conservative = negative)
- Four lines plotted:
  - **Solid red (House Republicans)**: Steady increase in conservatism over time
  - **Dashed red (Senate Republicans)**: Similar upward trend
  - **Solid blue (House Democrats)**: Decline in conservatism, becoming less conservative over time
  - **Dashed blue (Senate Democrats)**: Mirrors House Democrats' trend
- Key annotation: Gap between parties' ideologies labeled **"Greatest gap"** around 2020
- Arrows indicate increasing conservatism of Republicans and decreasing conservatism of Democrats over the century

**Description 137: Party-Line Voting (1790-2030)**
- Y-axis: Percentage of votes cast along party lines (60-100%)
- Red line fluctuates over time, showing periods of both high and low partisanship
- Recent years: **Sharp upward trend**, percentage nearing 100%
- Highlighted with circle and arrow pointing to it

**Description 138: US Polarization Index (1900-2030)**
- Y-axis: Polarization index (-0.6 to 1.0)
- Fluctuations over time with notable peaks around 1920s, 1940s, and 1970s
- Decline in polarization from 1980s to early 2000s
- Sharp upward trend starting around 2000, reaching **highest point by 2020**
- Arrow labeled **"Up equals More polarization; Worst in history"** points to steep rise after 2000

**Description 139: US-China Power Dynamics**
- First graph: **Country Power Indices** (1800-2020, 0-100%)
  - Red line (China): Declining from 1800 to mid-20th century, sharp rise after 2000
  - Blue line (United States): Increases steadily from 1800, peaks around 1950, slightly declines but remains high
- Second graph: **US-China Conflict Gauge** (1960-2020, -0.2 to 1.2)
  - Red line: Gradual increase in conflict from 1960
  - Notable spikes around 1990 and sharp rise after 2000, reaching highest point by 2020

**Description 140: Long-Term Economic and Life Expectancy Trends**
- First graph: **Global RGDP Per Capita (LN)** (logarithmic scale)
  - Line relatively flat from 1500 to late 1700s
  - Slight increase labeled **"Invention of capitalism (founding of Dutch Stock Exchange)"**
  - Sharp upward inflection during Industrial Revolution, continues rising steeply into 20th century
- Second graph: **Global Life Expectancy at Birth**
  - Dashed line before 1800 based on Great Britain's historical data
  - Fluctuates slightly due to events: "1557 influenza pandemic," "Thirty Years' War," "Third Plague pandemic"
  - Significant dip marked during **"WW1, Spanish flu pandemic"**
  - Steady rise after WW2, peaking during **"Baby Boom"**

